{"title_page": "Tim Thornton (bishop)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Reverend]]\n| name = Tim Thornton\n| image = Bishop at Lambeth at the 2019 Blessing the Thames Ceremony (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Thornton at the 2019 Blessing the Thames ceremony on [[London Bridge]]\n| title = {{nowrap|[[Bishop at Lambeth]],}} {{nowrap|[[Bishop to the Forces]]}} and {{nowrap|[[Bishop for the Falkland Islands]]}}\n| church = [[Church of England]]\n| diocese = <!--none-->\n| term = {{nowrap|6 September}} 2017{{snd}}present\n| predecessor = [[Nigel Stock (bishop)|Nigel Stock]]\n| other_post = [[Bishop of Sherborne]] {{nowrap|(2001\u20132008)}}<br />[[Bishop of Truro]] {{nowrap|(2009\u20132017)}}<br />[[Lord Spiritual]] {{nowrap|(2013\u20132017)}}\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination = 1980\n| consecration = {{nowrap|21 October}} 2001\n| consecrated_by = [[George Carey]]\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|4|14|df=y}}\n| nationality = British\n| religion = [[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n| residence = [[Lambeth Palace]]\n| spouse = Si\u00e2n\n| children = 2\n| alma_mater = [[University of Southampton]]<br />[[King's College London]]\n}}\n\n'''Timothy Martin Thornton''' (born 14 April 1957) is a British [[Anglican]] bishop. Since 6 September 2017, he has been [[Bishop at Lambeth]], [[Bishop to the Forces]], and [[Bishop for the Falkland Islands]].<ref name=\"lam\">[http://www.archbishopofcanterbury.org/articles.php/5887/bishop-tim-thornton-commissioned-as-new-bishop-at-lambeth Lambeth Palace \u2014 Tim Thornton commissioned as new Bishop at Lambeth] (Accessed 9 September 2017)</ref> He was previously the [[area bishop|area]] [[Bishop of Sherborne]] from 2001 to 2008, the [[diocesan bishop|diocesan]] [[Bishop of Truro]] (2009\u20132017), and a Member of the [[House of Lords]] (2013\u20132017).<ref>[http://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/lords/new-lords/ Parliament: New Lords, 31 January 2013.]</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nThornton was born on 14 April 1957.<ref name=\"ww\">{{Who's Who | surname = Thornton | othernames = Timothy Martin | id = U42249 | volume = 2017 | edition = November 2016 online | accessed = 31 May 2017 }}</ref> He was educated at [[Devonport High School for Boys]], an all-boys [[grammar school]] in [[Plymouth]], Devon.<ref name=\"Western Morning News\" /> He studied [[theology]] at the [[University of Southampton]], and graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA) degree in 1978.<ref name=\"Western Morning News\" /><ref name=\"Crockford entry\">{{Crockford| surname = Thornton | forenames = Timothy Martin | id = 25000 | accessed = 26 December 2015}}</ref> That year, he entered [[St Stephen's House, Oxford]], an [[Anglo-Catholic]] [[theological college]], to train for the priesthood.<ref name=\"Crockford entry\" /> He later studied at [[King's College London]] graduating with an MA in 1997.<ref>Debrett's People of Today London, [[Debrett's]], 2008 {{ISBN|978-1-870520-95-9}}</ref>\n\n==Ordained ministry==\nHe was ordained in the [[Church of England]]: made a deacon at [[Petertide]] 1980 (29 June)<ref>{{Church Times | title = Petertide ordinations | archive = 1980_07_04_005 | issue = 6125 | date = 4 July 1980 | page = 5 | accessed = 7 May 2019 }}</ref> and ordained a priest the Petertide following (28 June 1981), both times by [[Colin James (bishop)|Colin James]], [[Bishop of Wakefield (diocese)|Bishop of Wakefield]] at [[Wakefield Cathedral]].<ref>{{Church Times | title = Petertide ordinations | archive = 1981_07_03_016 | issue = 6177 | date = 3 July 1981 | page = 16 | accessed = 7 May 2019 }}</ref> He began his ministry with a [[Curate|curacy]] at [[Todmorden]] and then as [[priest-in-charge]] at [[Walsden]]. He then became [[Chaplain|bishop's chaplain]] to [[David Hope, Baron Hope of Thornes|David Hope]]: successively in the [[Diocese of Wakefield]] and the [[Diocese of London]]. From 1994 until 1998 he was [[Dean (education)|Principal]] of the [[North Thames Ministerial Training Course]]. His final post before his ordination to the [[Episcopal See|episcopate]] was as the [[vicar]] of [[Kensington]].\n\n===Episcopal ministry===\nOn 21 October 2001, Thornton was [[consecrated]] a [[bishop]] by [[George Carey]], the then Archbishop of Canterbury, at [[Southwark Cathedral]].<ref>{{Church Times | title = News (in brief): Say what you really think, two new bishops told | archive = 2001_10_26_004 | issue = 7236 | date = 26 October 2001 | page = 4 | accessed = 11 October 2015 }}</ref> From 2001 to 2008, he served as the [[Bishop of Sherborne]], an [[area bishop]] of the [[Diocese of Salisbury]].<ref>[http://anglicancommunion.org/tour/cathedral.cfm?IDNUMBER=14755&view=alpha Anglican communion]</ref><ref>[http://www.number-10.gov.uk/output/Page2702.asp Official announcement] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122033446/http://www.number-10.gov.uk/output/Page2702.asp |date=22 November 2008 }}</ref> He was installed as [[Bishop of Truro]] at [[Truro Cathedral]] on 7 March 2009.\n\nIn 2013, Thornton became eligible to join the [[Lords Spiritual]] in the [[House of Lords]] upon the retirement of [[Nigel McCulloch]], the then Bishop of Manchester, as the next longest serving diocesan bishop.<ref name=\"Western Morning News\">{{cite news|title=Truro Bishop Tim takes up his seat in Lords|url=http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Truro-Bishop-Tim-takes-seat-Lords/story-18778325-detail/story.html|accessdate=26 December 2015|work=Western Morning News|date=23 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226100812/http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Truro-Bishop-Tim-takes-seat-Lords/story-18778325-detail/story.html|archive-date=26 December 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"bio - HoL\">{{cite web|title=Bishop of Truro|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/bishop-of-truro/4271|website=House of Lords|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> He officially became a Lord spiritual on 31 January 2013;<ref name=\"bio - HoL\" /> however, he did not take his seat until he was [[Introduction (House of Lords)|introduced to the House]] in April 2013.<ref name=\"Western Morning News\" />\n\nOn 4 April 2017, it was announced that he was to resign his see to become [[Bishop at Lambeth]], the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]]'s episcopal chief of staff at [[Lambeth Palace]], in September 2017.<ref name=\"tr-res\">[http://www.archbishopofcanterbury.org/articles.php/5852/bishop-tim-thornton-announced-as-new-bishop-at-lambeth Lambeth Palace \u2014 Tim Thornton announced as new Bishop at Lambeth] (Accessed 4 April 2017)</ref>\n\n===Other work===\nThornton has chaired the Board of Trustees of [[The Children's Society]] from 2010. He was a trustee of the [[Church Army]] 2000\u20132008. He is a trustee of the following Cornish charities: Volunteer Cornwall, BF Adventure (formerly Bishops Forum), Cornwall Community Foundation.<ref>[http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/bishop-of-truro/4271 UK Parliament website: Biographies of Peers]</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Thornton was the Anglican delegate to the [[Fourteenth Ordinary General Assembly of the Synod of Bishops|XIV Ordinary General Assembly of the (Roman Catholic) Synod of Bishops]].\n\n===Elliott Review controversy===\nIn March 2016, Thornton was cited in a ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' report<ref>{{cite news|title=Damning report reveals Church of England's failure to act on abuse|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/15/damning-report-reveals-church-of-england-failure-to-act-on-abuse|accessdate=8 October 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|date=15 March 2016}}</ref> on the [https://www.churchofengland.org/clergy-office-holders/safeguarding-children-vulnerable-adults/media-statements-newsletters/elliott-review-findings.aspx Elliott Review] as one of several senior figures who had received a disclosure of [[child sex abuse]] but had \"no recollection\". The review, led by [http://ianelliottsafeguarding.com/ Ian Elliott], found this lack of memory difficult to countenance. \"What is surprising about this is that he (the survivor) would be speaking about a serious and sadistic sexual assault allegedly perpetrated by a senior member of the hierarchy. The fact that these conversations could be forgotten about is hard to accept,\" Elliott wrote. The survivor had tried repeatedly to alert the [[Justin Welby|Archbishop]]'s office to critical concerns arising from these denials, but was ignored on the instruction of the church's [[Ecclesiastical|insurers]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Church cut contact with child abuse victim on order of insurers|url=http://www.secularism.org.uk/news/2016/03/church-cut-contact-with-child-abuse-victim-on-order-of-insurers|accessdate=8 October 2016|publisher=National Secular Society|date=16 March 2016}}</ref> The resulting Elliott Review led to damning headlines across the UK and world media<ref>{{cite news|title=Welby\u2019s staff ignored abuse to save money|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/uk/article4714329.ece|accessdate=8 October 2016|newspaper=The Times|date=16 March 2016}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Church of England figures ignored 'sadistic' abuse of 15-year-old boy by senior priest for 40 years, report says|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/church-of-england-figures-ignored-sadistic-abuse-of-15-year-old-boy-by-senior-priest-for-40-years-a6932641.html|accessdate=8 October 2016|newspaper=The Independent|date=15 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Church of England vows to change after damning report on abuse|url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/70612/church-of-england-vows-to-change-after-damning-report-on-abuse|accessdate=8 October 2016|magazine=The Week|date=16 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Church of England 'will change' after abuse report|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-35813744|accessdate=8 October 2016|work=BBC News|date=15 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Archbishop of Canterbury's office criticised for 'ignoring' abuse complaints|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/12195083/Archbishop-of-Canterburys-office-criticised-for-ignoring-abuse-complaints.html|accessdate=8 October 2016|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=15 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Church of England ignored sex abuse victim for decades|url=https://www.neweurope.eu/article/church-england-ignored-sex-abuse-victim-decades/|accessdate=8 October 2016|publisher=New Europe|date=16 March 2016}}</ref> and kickstarted significant cultural and structural change in the Church of England's response to sex abuse cases. The review called for all bishops to be retrained.<ref>{{cite news|title=Senior clergy must be retrained to deal with sex abuse disclosures|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/15/church-of-england-senior-clergy-must-be-retrained-sex-abuse-disclosures-sarah-mullally|accessdate=9 October 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|date=15 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Church of England clergy need 'systematic retraining' on dealing with sex abuse reports|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/church-england-clergy-need-systematic-retraining-dealing-sex-abuse-reports-1560174|accessdate=9 October 2016|newspaper=International Business Times|date=15 May 2016}}</ref> The Archbishop of Canterbury, [[Justin Welby]], reportedly said \"the situation is embarrassing and uncomfortable for the church.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Church of England Rocked by 'Deeply Disturbing' Sex Abuse Report|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/church-of-england-rocked-by-deeply-disturbing-sex-abuse-report-159294|accessdate=8 October 2016|newspaper=Christian Post|date=16 March 2016}}</ref> In an open letter the survivor urged Thornton to lead a call for [[repentance]] across the [[House of Bishops]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe\u2019s letter to the House of Bishops of the Church of England|url=http://survivingchurch.org/2016/06/21/jos-letter-to-the-anglican-house-of-bishops/|website=Surviving Church|accessdate=21 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bishops must repent for inaction on child abuse, says survivor|url=https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2016/20-may/news/uk/bishops-must-repent-for-inaction-on-child-abuse-says-survivor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160520111732/https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2016/20-may/news/uk/bishops-must-repent-for-inaction-on-child-abuse-says-survivor|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 May 2016|accessdate=12 October 2016|publisher=Church Times|date=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs from October 2016, Thornton has sat on the Church of England's National Safeguarding Steering Group (NSSG)<ref>{{cite web|title=National Safeguarding Steering Group|url=https://www.churchofengland.org/sites/default/files/2017-11/NSSG%20Terms%20of%20Reference%20and%20Membership%20Nov%202017.pdf|website=Church of England|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=November 20 2017 \u2013 National Safeguarding Steering Group [NSSG] and National Safeguarding Panel [NSP] \u2013 Church of England|url=https://richardwsymonds.wordpress.com/2017/11/20/november-20-2017-national-safeguarding-steering-group-nssg-and-national-safeguarding-panel-nsp-church-of-england/|website=The Bell Society|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThornton is married to Si\u00e2n, one of Her Majesty's Inspectors of Education (HMI) in England.<ref name=\"Western Morning News\" /><ref name=\"cath\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20050206130007/http://www.trurocathedral.org.uk/day-to-day/news.html Truro Cathedral News]</ref> Together, they have two adult children.<ref name=\"Western Morning News\" /><ref name=\"no10\">[http://www.number10.gov.uk/Page2702 Number 10 \u2014 Suffragan See of Sherborne] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616041627/http://www.number10.gov.uk/Page2702 |date=16 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Styles==\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n*''[[The Reverend]]'' Tim Thornton (1980\u20132001)\n*''[[The Right Reverend]]'' Tim Thornton (2001\u2013present)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-rel|en}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[John Kirkham (bishop)|John Kirkham]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Sherborne]]|years=2001\u20132008}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Graham Kings]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Bill Ind]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Truro]]|years=2008\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Philip Mounstephen]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Nigel Stock (bishop)|Nigel Stock]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop at Lambeth]],<br />[[Bishop to the Forces]] and<br />[[Bishop for the Falkland Islands]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Bishops of Sherborne}}\n{{Bishops of Truro}}\n{{Bishops at Lambeth}}\n{{Bishops to the Forces}}\n{{Archbishop of Canterbury}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thornton, Timothy Martin}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Southampton]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Stephen's House, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Sherborne]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Truro]]\n[[Category:Lords Spiritual]]\n[[Category:21st-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:People educated at Devonport High School for Boys]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:English Anglo-Catholics]]\n[[Category:Bishops at Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Bishops to the Forces]]\n[[Category:Bishops of the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:Church Army people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Reverend]]\n| name = Tim Thornton\n| image = Bishop at Lambeth at the 2019 Blessing the Thames Ceremony (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Thornton at the 2019 Blessing the Thames ceremony on [[London Bridge]]\n| title = {{nowrap|[[Bishop at Lambeth]],}} {{nowrap|[[Bishop to the Forces]]}} and {{nowrap|[[Bishop for the Falkland Islands]]}}\n| church = [[Church of England]]\n| diocese = <!--none-->\n| term = {{nowrap|6 September}} 2017{{snd}}present\n| predecessor = [[Nigel Stock (bishop)|Nigel Stock]]\n| other_post = [[Bishop of Sherborne]] {{nowrap|(2001\u20132008)}}<br />[[Bishop of Truro]] {{nowrap|(2009\u20132017)}}<br />[[Lord Spiritual]] {{nowrap|(2013\u20132017)}}\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination = 1980\n| consecration = {{nowrap|21 October}} 2001\n| consecrated_by = [[George Carey]]\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|4|14|df=y}}\n| nationality = British\n| religion = [[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n| residence = [[Lambeth Palace]]\n| spouse = Si\u00e2n\n| children = 2\n| alma_mater = [[University of Southampton]]<br />[[King's College London]]\n}}\n\n'''Timothy Martin Thornton''' (born 14 April 1957) is a British [[Anglican]] bishop. Since 6 September 2017, he has been [[Bishop at Lambeth]], [[Bishop to the Forces]], and [[Bishop for the Falkland Islands]].<ref name=\"lam\">[http://www.archbishopofcanterbury.org/articles.php/5887/bishop-tim-thornton-commissioned-as-new-bishop-at-lambeth Lambeth Palace \u2014 Tim Thornton commissioned as new Bishop at Lambeth] (Accessed 9 September 2017)</ref> He was previously the [[area bishop|area]] [[Bishop of Sherborne]] from 2001 to 2008, the [[diocesan bishop|diocesan]] [[Bishop of Truro]] (2009\u20132017), and a Member of the [[House of Lords]] (2013\u20132017).<ref>[http://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/lords/new-lords/ Parliament: New Lords, 31 January 2013.]</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nThornton was born on 14 April 1957.<ref name=\"ww\">{{Who's Who | surname = Thornton | othernames = Timothy Martin | id = U42249 | volume = 2017 | edition = November 2016 online | accessed = 31 May 2017 }}</ref> He was educated at [[Devonport High School for Boys]], an all-boys [[grammar school]] in [[Plymouth]], Devon.<ref name=\"Western Morning News\" /> He studied [[theology]] at the [[University of Southampton]], and graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] (BA) degree in 1978.<ref name=\"Western Morning News\" /><ref name=\"Crockford entry\">{{Crockford| surname = Thornton | forenames = Timothy Martin | id = 25000 | accessed = 26 December 2015}}</ref> That year, he entered [[St Stephen's House, Oxford]], an [[Anglo-Catholic]] [[theological college]], to train for the priesthood.<ref name=\"Crockford entry\" /> He later studied at [[King's College London]] graduating with an MA in 1997.<ref>Debrett's People of Today London, [[Debrett's]], 2008 {{ISBN|978-1-870520-95-9}}</ref>\n\n==Ordained ministry==\nHe was ordained in the [[Church of England]]: made a deacon at [[Petertide]] 1980 (29 June)<ref>{{Church Times | title = Petertide ordinations | archive = 1980_07_04_005 | issue = 6125 | date = 4 July 1980 | page = 5 | accessed = 7 May 2019 }}</ref> and ordained a priest the Petertide following (28 June 1981), both times by [[Colin James (bishop)|Colin James]], [[Bishop of Wakefield (diocese)|Bishop of Wakefield]] at [[Wakefield Cathedral]].<ref>{{Church Times | title = Petertide ordinations | archive = 1981_07_03_016 | issue = 6177 | date = 3 July 1981 | page = 16 | accessed = 7 May 2019 }}</ref> He began his ministry with a [[Curate|curacy]] at [[Todmorden]] and then as [[priest-in-charge]] at [[Walsden]]. He then became [[Chaplain|bishop's chaplain]] to [[David Hope, Baron Hope of Thornes|David Hope]]: successively in the [[Diocese of Wakefield]] and the [[Diocese of London]]. From 1994 until 1998 he was [[Dean (education)|Principal]] of the [[North Thames Ministerial Training Course]]. His final post before his ordination to the [[Episcopal See|episcopate]] was as the [[vicar]] of [[Kensington]].\n\n===Episcopal ministry===\nOn 21 October 2001, Thornton was [[consecrated]] a [[bishop]] by [[George Carey]], the then Archbishop of Canterbury, at [[Southwark Cathedral]].<ref>{{Church Times | title = News (in brief): Say what you really think, two new bishops told | archive = 2001_10_26_004 | issue = 7236 | date = 26 October 2001 | page = 4 | accessed = 11 October 2015 }}</ref> From 2001 to 2008, he served as the [[Bishop of Sherborne]], an [[area bishop]] of the [[Diocese of Salisbury]].<ref>[http://anglicancommunion.org/tour/cathedral.cfm?IDNUMBER=14755&view=alpha Anglican communion]</ref><ref>[http://www.number-10.gov.uk/output/Page2702.asp Official announcement] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122033446/http://www.number-10.gov.uk/output/Page2702.asp |date=22 November 2008 }}</ref> He was installed as [[Bishop of Truro]] at [[Truro Cathedral]] on 7 March 2009.\n\nIn 2013, Thornton became eligible to join the [[Lords Spiritual]] in the [[House of Lords]] upon the retirement of [[Nigel McCulloch]], the then Bishop of Manchester, as the next longest serving diocesan bishop.<ref name=\"Western Morning News\">{{cite news|title=Truro Bishop Tim takes up his seat in Lords|url=http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Truro-Bishop-Tim-takes-seat-Lords/story-18778325-detail/story.html|accessdate=26 December 2015|work=Western Morning News|date=23 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226100812/http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Truro-Bishop-Tim-takes-seat-Lords/story-18778325-detail/story.html|archive-date=26 December 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"bio - HoL\">{{cite web|title=Bishop of Truro|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/bishop-of-truro/4271|website=House of Lords|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> He officially became a Lord spiritual on 31 January 2013;<ref name=\"bio - HoL\" /> however, he did not take his seat until he was [[Introduction (House of Lords)|introduced to the House]] in April 2013.<ref name=\"Western Morning News\" />\n\nOn 4 April 2017, it was announced that he was to resign his see to become [[Bishop at Lambeth]], the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]]'s episcopal chief of staff at [[Lambeth Palace]], in September 2017.<ref name=\"tr-res\">[http://www.archbishopofcanterbury.org/articles.php/5852/bishop-tim-thornton-announced-as-new-bishop-at-lambeth Lambeth Palace \u2014 Tim Thornton announced as new Bishop at Lambeth] (Accessed 4 April 2017)</ref>\n\n===Other work===\nThornton has chaired the Board of Trustees of [[The Children's Society]] from 2010. He was a trustee of the [[Church Army]] 2000-2008. He is a trustee of the following Cornish charities: Volunteer Cornwall, BF Adventure (formerly Bishops Forum), Cornwall Community Foundation.<ref>[http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/bishop-of-truro/4271 UK Parliament website: Biographies of Peers]</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Thornton was the Anglican delegate to the [[Fourteenth Ordinary General Assembly of the Synod of Bishops|XIV Ordinary General Assembly of the (Roman Catholic) Synod of Bishops]].\n\n===Elliott Review controversy===\nIn March 2016, Thornton was cited in a ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' report<ref>{{cite news|title=Damning report reveals Church of England's failure to act on abuse|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/15/damning-report-reveals-church-of-england-failure-to-act-on-abuse|accessdate=8 October 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|date=15 March 2016}}</ref> on the [https://www.churchofengland.org/clergy-office-holders/safeguarding-children-vulnerable-adults/media-statements-newsletters/elliott-review-findings.aspx Elliott Review] as one of several senior figures who had received a disclosure of [[child sex abuse]] but had \"no recollection\". The review, led by [http://ianelliottsafeguarding.com/ Ian Elliott], found this lack of memory difficult to countenance. \"What is surprising about this is that he (the survivor) would be speaking about a serious and sadistic sexual assault allegedly perpetrated by a senior member of the hierarchy. The fact that these conversations could be forgotten about is hard to accept,\" Elliott wrote. The survivor had tried repeatedly to alert the [[Justin Welby|Archbishop]]'s office to critical concerns arising from these denials, but was ignored on the instruction of the church's [[Ecclesiastical|insurers]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Church cut contact with child abuse victim on order of insurers|url=http://www.secularism.org.uk/news/2016/03/church-cut-contact-with-child-abuse-victim-on-order-of-insurers|accessdate=8 October 2016|publisher=National Secular Society|date=16 March 2016}}</ref> The resulting Elliott Review led to damning headlines across the UK and world media<ref>{{cite news|title=Welby\u2019s staff ignored abuse to save money|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/uk/article4714329.ece|accessdate=8 October 2016|newspaper=The Times|date=16 March 2016}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Church of England figures ignored 'sadistic' abuse of 15-year-old boy by senior priest for 40 years, report says|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/church-of-england-figures-ignored-sadistic-abuse-of-15-year-old-boy-by-senior-priest-for-40-years-a6932641.html|accessdate=8 October 2016|newspaper=The Independent|date=15 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Church of England vows to change after damning report on abuse|url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/70612/church-of-england-vows-to-change-after-damning-report-on-abuse|accessdate=8 October 2016|magazine=The Week|date=16 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Church of England 'will change' after abuse report|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-35813744|accessdate=8 October 2016|work=BBC News|date=15 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Archbishop of Canterbury's office criticised for 'ignoring' abuse complaints|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/12195083/Archbishop-of-Canterburys-office-criticised-for-ignoring-abuse-complaints.html|accessdate=8 October 2016|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=15 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Church of England ignored sex abuse victim for decades|url=https://www.neweurope.eu/article/church-england-ignored-sex-abuse-victim-decades/|accessdate=8 October 2016|publisher=New Europe|date=16 March 2016}}</ref> and kickstarted significant cultural and structural change in the Church of England's response to sex abuse cases. The review called for all bishops to be retrained.<ref>{{cite news|title=Senior clergy must be retrained to deal with sex abuse disclosures|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/may/15/church-of-england-senior-clergy-must-be-retrained-sex-abuse-disclosures-sarah-mullally|accessdate=9 October 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|date=15 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Church of England clergy need 'systematic retraining' on dealing with sex abuse reports|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/church-england-clergy-need-systematic-retraining-dealing-sex-abuse-reports-1560174|accessdate=9 October 2016|newspaper=International Business Times|date=15 May 2016}}</ref> The Archbishop of Canterbury, [[Justin Welby]], reportedly said \"the situation is embarrassing and uncomfortable for the church.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Church of England Rocked by 'Deeply Disturbing' Sex Abuse Report|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/church-of-england-rocked-by-deeply-disturbing-sex-abuse-report-159294|accessdate=8 October 2016|newspaper=Christian Post|date=16 March 2016}}</ref> In an open letter the survivor urged Thornton to lead a call for [[repentance]] across the [[House of Bishops]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe\u2019s letter to the House of Bishops of the Church of England|url=http://survivingchurch.org/2016/06/21/jos-letter-to-the-anglican-house-of-bishops/|website=Surviving Church|accessdate=21 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bishops must repent for inaction on child abuse, says survivor|url=https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2016/20-may/news/uk/bishops-must-repent-for-inaction-on-child-abuse-says-survivor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160520111732/https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2016/20-may/news/uk/bishops-must-repent-for-inaction-on-child-abuse-says-survivor|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 May 2016|accessdate=12 October 2016|publisher=Church Times|date=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs from October 2016, Thornton has sat on the Church of England's National Safeguarding Steering Group (NSSG)<ref>{{cite web|title=National Safeguarding Steering Group|url=https://www.churchofengland.org/sites/default/files/2017-11/NSSG%20Terms%20of%20Reference%20and%20Membership%20Nov%202017.pdf|website=Church of England|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=November 20 2017 \u2013 National Safeguarding Steering Group [NSSG] and National Safeguarding Panel [NSP] \u2013 Church of England|url=https://richardwsymonds.wordpress.com/2017/11/20/november-20-2017-national-safeguarding-steering-group-nssg-and-national-safeguarding-panel-nsp-church-of-england/|website=The Bell Society|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThornton is married to Si\u00e2n, one of Her Majesty\u2019s Inspectors of Education (HMI) in England.<ref name=\"Western Morning News\" /><ref name=\"cath\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20050206130007/http://www.trurocathedral.org.uk/day-to-day/news.html Truro Cathedral News]</ref> Together, they have two adult children.<ref name=\"Western Morning News\" /><ref name=\"no10\">[http://www.number10.gov.uk/Page2702 Number 10 \u2014 Suffragan See of Sherborne] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616041627/http://www.number10.gov.uk/Page2702 |date=16 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Styles==\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n*''[[The Reverend]]'' Tim Thornton (1980\u20132001)\n*''[[The Right Reverend]]'' Tim Thornton (2001\u2013present)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-rel|en}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[John Kirkham (bishop)|John Kirkham]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Sherborne]]|years=2001\u20132008}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Graham Kings]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Bill Ind]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Truro]]|years=2008\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Philip Mounstephen]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Nigel Stock (bishop)|Nigel Stock]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop at Lambeth]],<br />[[Bishop to the Forces]] and<br />[[Bishop for the Falkland Islands]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Bishops of Sherborne}}\n{{Bishops of Truro}}\n{{Bishops at Lambeth}}\n{{Bishops to the Forces}}\n{{Archbishop of Canterbury}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thornton, Timothy Martin}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Southampton]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Stephen's House, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Sherborne]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Truro]]\n[[Category:Lords Spiritual]]\n[[Category:21st-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:People educated at Devonport High School for Boys]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:English Anglo-Catholics]]\n[[Category:Bishops at Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Bishops to the Forces]]\n[[Category:Bishops of the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:Church Army people]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's, 2000-2008 \u2192 2000\u20132008", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tim_Thornton_(bishop)"}
{"title_page": "Jet aircraft", "text_new": "{{short description|Aircraft class powered by jet propulsion engines}}\n[[File:Boeing 707-340C, JAT - Yugoslav Airlines AN1046903.jpg|thumb|[[Boeing 707]] of [[Jat Airways|JAT Airways]].]]\n[[File:RAF Eurofighter EF-2000 Typhoon F2 Lofting-1.jpg\n|thumb|[[RAF]] [[Eurofighter Typhoon F2] ]]\n\nA '''jet aircraft''' (or simply '''jet''') is an [[aircraft]] (nearly always a [[fixed-wing aircraft]]) propelled by [[jet engine]]s.\n\nWhereas the engines in [[Propeller (aircraft)|propeller-powered aircraft]] generally achieve their maximum efficiency at much lower speeds and altitudes, jet engines and aircraft achieve maximum efficiency at speeds close to or even well above the [[speed of sound]]. Jet aircraft generally cruise at faster than about [[Mach number|Mach]] 0.8 (609&nbsp;mph, 981&nbsp;km/h or 273&nbsp;m/s) at altitudes around {{convert|10000|-|15000|m|ft}} or more.\n\n[[Frank Whittle]], an [[English people|English]] inventor and [[RAF]] officer, developed the concept of the jet engine in 1928,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwn.org.uk/heritage/people/whittle/biography.html|title=Sir Frank Whittle - Jet Engine Inventor - Born In Coventry|first=Chris Studman for|last=CWN|website=www.cwn.org.uk|accessdate=6 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020155022/http://www.cwn.org.uk/heritage/people/whittle/biography.html|archivedate=20 October 2017}}</ref> and [[Hans von Ohain]] in Germany developed the concept independently in the early 1930s. He wrote in February 1936 to [[Ernst Heinkel]], who led the construction of the world's first [[turbojet]] aircraft and jet plane [[Heinkel He 178]].\n\nHenri Coand\u0103 is the real inventor of the jet plane.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ohain USAF He 178 page61.jpg|thumb|[[Heinkel He 178]], in August 1939 the world's first aircraft to fly purely on turbojet power]]\n[[File:Caproni foto.jpg|thumb|[[Caproni Campini N1]] in flight]]\n\nAfter the first instance of powered flight, a large number of jet engine factories were suggested. [[Ren\u00e9 Lorin]], Morize, Harris proposed systems for creating a jet efflux.<ref>[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1941/1941%20-%202221.html Jet Propulsion of Aircraft Part III] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105190203/http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1941/1941%20-%202221.html |date=2012-11-05}} G Geoffrey Smith ''Flight'' September 25th 1941</ref> In 1910 the [[Romanian people|Romanian]] inventor [[Henri Coand\u0103]] filed a patent on a jet propulsion system which used piston-engine exhaust gases to add heat to an otherwise pure air stream compressed by rotating fan blades in a duct. It was installed in his [[Coand\u0103-1910]] but this craft probably never flew.\n\nRocket-powered jet aircraft were pioneered in Germany. The first aircraft to fly under rocket power was the [[Lippisch Ente]], in 1928.<ref>[http://www.daviddarling.info/encyclopedia/L/Lippisch_Ente.htm \"Lippisch Ente.\"]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}} ''The Internet Encyclopedia of Science: Experimental Aircraft.'' Retrieved: 26 September 2011.</ref> The Ente had previously been flown as a glider. The next year, in 1929, the [[Opel RAK.1]] became the first purpose-built rocket plane to fly.\n\nThe [[turbojet]] was invented in 1939, independently by [[Frank Whittle]] and later [[Hans von Ohain]]. The first turbojet aircraft to fly was the [[Heinkel He 178]] V1 first [[prototype]] of the [[Nazi Germany|German]] Air Force, the ''[[Luftwaffe]]'', on August 27, 1939 in [[Rostock]] (Germany).<ref>Warsitz, Lutz: [http://www.pen-and-sword.co.uk/?product_id=1762 ''The First Jet Pilot \u2013 The Story of German Test Pilot Erich Warsitz'' (p. 125), Pen and Sword Books Ltd., England, 2009] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100603014802/http://www.pen-and-sword.co.uk/?product_id=1762 |date=2010-06-03}}</ref>\n\nThe first flight of a jet-engined aircraft to come to public attention was the [[Kingdom of Italy|Italian]] [[Caproni Campini N.1]] [[motorjet]] prototype that flew on August 27, 1940.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1941/1941%20-%201950.html|title=''Flight'' 28 August 1941|website=flightglobal.com |accessdate=6 May 2018|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020161845/https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1941/1941%20-%201950.html|archivedate=20 October 2017}}</ref> It was the first jet aircraft recognised by the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration A\u00e9ronautique Internationale]] (at the time the German He 178 program was still kept secret). Campini had proposed the motorjet in 1932.\n\nThe British experimental [[Gloster E.28/39]] first took to the air on May 15, 1941, powered by [[Sir Frank Whittle]]'s turbojet.<ref>[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1949/1949%20-%201789.html? \"No Airscrew Necessary...\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025175115/http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1949/1949%20-%201789.html |date=2012-10-25 }} ''Flight''(flightglobal.com), 27 October 1949 p554</ref> The [[United States]] produced the [[Bell P-59 Airacomet|Bell XP-59A]] using two examples of a version of the Whittle engine built by [[General Electric]], which flew on October 1, 1942. The Meteor was the first production jet as it entered production a few months before the Me 262,{{Citation needed|date=March 2016}} which itself had been in development since before the start of the war as Projekt 1065.\n\n[[File:Me 262 flight show at ILA 2006.jpg|thumb|left|A modern reproduction of the Me 262 in flight in 2006. The first operational turbojet aircraft, the Messerschmitt Me 262 entered service in April 1944.]]\n\nThe first operational [[fighter aircraft|jet fighter]] was the [[Messerschmitt Me 262]],<ref>Hecht, Heinrich. ''The World's First Turbojet Fighter \u2013 Messerschmitt Me 262''. Atglen, Pennsylvania: Schiffer Publishing, 1990. {{ISBN|0-88740-234-8}}.{{Page needed|date=October 2010}}</ref> manufactured by Germany during World War II, which entered service on 19 April 1944 with Erprobungskommando 262 at Lechfeld just south of Augsburg. It was the fastest conventional aircraft of [[World War II]]&nbsp;\u2013 although there were faster aircraft propelled by unconventional means, such as the rocket-powered [[Messerschmitt Me 163 Komet]]. The [[Messerschmitt Me 262]] had first flown on April 18, 1941, with initial plans drawn up by Dr Waldemar Voigt's design team in April 1939, but mass production did not start until early 1944 with the first squadrons operational that year, too late for a decisive effect on the outcome of the war.\n\n[[File:Gloster Meteor III ExCC.jpg|thumb|right|Gloster Meteor F.3s. The [[Gloster Meteor]] was the first British jet fighter and the [[Allies of World War II|Allies']] only jet aircraft to achieve combat operations during World War II.]]\n\nAround this time, mid 1944, the United Kingdom's [[Gloster Meteor]] was being committed to defence of the UK against the [[V-1 flying bomb]]&nbsp;\u2013 itself a [[pulsejet]]-powered aircraft&nbsp;and direct ancestor of the [[cruise missile]]\u2013 and then ground-attack operations over Europe in the last months of the war. In 1944 Germany introduced into service the [[Arado Ar 234]] jet reconnaissance and bomber, though chiefly used in the former role, with the [[Heinkel He 162]] ''Spatz'' single-jet [[light fighter]]  premiering as 1944 ended. USSR tested its own [[Bereznyak-Isayev BI-1]] in 1942, but the project was scrapped by [[Joseph Stalin]] in 1945. The [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] also developed jet aircraft in 1945, including the [[Nakajima Kikka|Nakajima J9Y Kikka]], a modified, and slightly smaller version of the Me 262 that had folding wings. By the end of 1945, the US had introduced their first jet fighter, the [[Lockheed P-80 Shooting Star]] into service and the UK its second fighter design, the [[de Havilland Vampire]].\n\n[[File:Lufthansa B737-330 (D-ABXS) approaching London Heathrow Airport.jpg|thumb|left|The Boeing 737-300, part of the [[Boeing 737]] family is the most produced jet aircraft that is still operating.]]\n\nThe US introduced the [[North American B-45 Tornado]], their first jet bomber, into service in 1948. Although capable of carrying nuclear weapons it was used for reconnaissance over Korea. On November 8, 1950, during the [[Korean War]], [[United States Air Force]] Lt. Russell J. Brown, flying in an [[P-80 Shooting Star|F-80]], intercepted two [[North Korea]]n [[MiG-15]]s near the [[Yalu River]] and shot them down in the first jet-to-jet [[dogfight]] in history. The UK put the [[English Electric Canberra]] into service in 1951 as a [[light bomber]]. It was designed to fly higher and faster than any [[Interceptor aircraft|interceptor]].\n\n[[File:BOAC Comet 1952 Entebbe.jpg|thumb|[[British Overseas Airways Corporation|BOAC]] Comet 1 was the first passenger jet airliner]]\n[[File:Boeing 707-138B Qantas Jett Clipper Ella N707JT.jpg|thumb|Boeing 707]]\n\n[[BOAC]] operated the first commercial jet service, from [[London]] to [[Johannesburg]], in 1952 with the [[de Havilland Comet]] [[jet airliner|jetliner]]. This highly innovative aircraft travelled far faster and higher than the propeller aircraft, was much quieter, smoother, and had stylish blended wings containing hidden jet engines. However, due to a design defect, and use of aluminium alloys, the aircraft suffered catastrophic [[metal fatigue]] which led to several crashes.<ref name=\"ruled\">Jet! When Britain Ruled the Skies - BBC</ref>\n\nThe series of crashes gave time for the [[Boeing 707]] to enter service in 1958 and this came to dominate the market for civilian airliners. The underslung engines were found to be advantageous in the event of a propellant leak, and so the 707 looked rather different from the Comet: the 707 has a shape that is effectively the same as that of contemporary aircraft, with marked commonality still evident today for example with the [[Boeing 737|737]] (fuselage) and [[Airbus A340|A340]] (single deck, swept wing, four below-wing engines).\n\n[[Turbofan]] aircraft began entering service in the 1950s and 1960s, bringing far greater [[fuel efficiency]], and this is the type of jet in widespread use today.\n[[File:Tu-144LL_in_flight.jpg|thumb|[[Tu-144]],  the world's first commercial [[supersonic transport]] aircraft (SST) ]]\n\nThe [[Tu-144]] [[supersonic transport]] was the fastest commercial jet plane at Mach 2.35 (1,555&nbsp;mph, 2,503&nbsp;km/h). It went into service in 1975, but soon stopped flying. The Mach 2 [[Concorde]] aircraft entered service in 1976 and flew for 27 years.\n\nThe fastest military jet plane was the [[SR-71 Blackbird]] at Mach 3.35 (2,275&nbsp;mph, 3,661&nbsp;km/h).\n\n==Other jets==\nMost people use the term 'jet aircraft' to denote gas turbine based [[airbreathing jet engine]]s, but rockets and scramjets are both also propelled by jet propulsion.\n\n[[Cruise missile]]s are single-use unmanned jet aircraft, powered predominately by ramjets or turbojets or sometimes turbofans, but they will often have a rocket propulsion system for initial propulsion.\n\nThe fastest airbreathing jet aircraft is the unmanned [[NASA X-43|X-43]] scramjet at around Mach 9\u201310.\n\nThe fastest manned (rocket) aircraft is the [[X-15]] at Mach 6.85.\n\nThe [[Space Shuttle]], while far faster than the X-43 or X-15, was not regarded as an aircraft during ascent as it was carried [[ballistics|ballistically]] by rocket thrust, rather than the air. During re-entry it was classed (like a glider) as an unpowered aircraft. The first flight was in 1981.\n\nThe [[Bell 533]] (1964), [[Lockheed XH-51]] (1965), and [[Sikorsky S-69]] (1977-1981) are examples of [[compound helicopter]] designs where jet exhaust added to forward thrust.<ref name=ieee>{{cite web|url= https://spectrum.ieee.org/aerospace/aviation/the-fastest-helicopter-on-earth |title=The Fastest Helicopter on Earth |authors=Thomas Lawrence and David Jenney|publisher=[[IEEE Spectrum]] |date=31 Aug 2010|accessdate=1 August 2017 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170130223834/https://spectrum.ieee.org/aerospace/aviation/the-fastest-helicopter-on-earth |archivedate=30 January 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Hiller YH-32 Hornet]] and [[Fairey Ultra-light Helicopter]] were among the many helicopters where the rotors were driven by [[tip jet]]s.\n\nJet-powered [[Wingsuit flying|wingsuits]] exist - powered by model aircraft jet engines - but of short duration and needing to be launched at height.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2013/07/how-to-fly-like-jetman/|title=\u2018Jetman\u2019 Yves Rossy Shows Us How to Fly His Carbon Fiber Jet Wing|publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=31 July 2013 |accessdate=1 August 2017 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170102151845/https://www.wired.com/2013/07/how-to-fly-like-jetman/ |archivedate=2 January 2017 |url-status= live  }}</ref>\n\n==Aerodynamics==\n[[File:McDonnell Douglas DC-10-30(ER), Biman Bangladesh AN0547320.jpg|thumb|A [[McDonnell Douglas DC-10]], an example of a [[Trijet]] configuration]]\nBecause of the way they work, the typical exhaust speed of jet engines is transonic or faster, therefore most jet aircraft need to fly at high speeds, either [[supersonic]] or speeds just below the speed of sound (\"[[transonic]]\") so as to achieve efficient flight. Aerodynamics is therefore an important consideration.\n\nJet aircraft are usually designed using the [[Whitcomb area rule]], which says that the total area of cross-section of the aircraft at any point along the aircraft from the nose must be approximately the same as that of a [[Sears-Haack body]]. A shape with that property minimises the production of shockwaves which would waste energy.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Jet engines==\n{{Main|Jet engine}}\n\nJet engines come in several main types:\n*[[turbojet]]\n*[[turbofan]] (which come in two main forms [[low bypass turbofan]] and [[high bypass turbofan]])\n*[[rocket]]\n\nThe different types are used for different purposes.\n\nRockets are the oldest type and are mainly used when extremely high speeds or extremely high altitudes are needed. Due to the extreme, typically [[hypersonic]], exhaust velocity and the necessity of oxidiser being carried on board, they consume propellant extremely quickly. For this reason, they are not practical for routine transportation.\n\nTurbojets are the second oldest type; it has a high, usually supersonic, exhaust speed and low frontal cross-section, and so is best suited to high-speed, usually supersonic, flight. Although once widely used, they are relatively inefficient compared to [[turboprop]] and turbofans for subsonic flight. The last major aircraft to use turbojets were Concorde and Tu-144 [[supersonic transport]]s.\n\nLow bypass turbofans have a lower exhaust speed than turbojets and are mostly used for high sonic, transonic, and low supersonic speeds. High bypass turbofans are used for subsonic aircraft and are quite efficient and are widely used for airliners.\n\n==Flying characteristics==\nJet aircraft fly considerably differently to propeller aircraft.\n\nOne difference is that jet engines respond relatively slowly. This complicates takeoff and landing maneuvers.\nIn particular, during takeoff, propeller aircraft engines blow air over their wings and that gives more lift and a shorter takeoff. These differences caught out some early BOAC Comet pilots.<ref name=ruled/>\n\n==Propulsive efficiency==\n{{main|Propulsive efficiency}}\nIn aircraft ''overall propulsive efficiency'' <math>\\eta</math> is the efficiency, in percent, with which the energy contained in a vehicle's propellant is converted into useful energy, to replace losses due to [[air drag]], gravity, and acceleration. It can also be stated as the proportion of the mechanical energy actually used to propel the aircraft. It is always less than 100% because of kinetic energy loss to the exhaust, and less-than-ideal efficiency of the propulsive mechanism, whether a [[Propeller (aircraft)|propeller]], a jet exhaust, or a fan. In addition, propulsive efficiency is greatly dependent on [[air density]] and airspeed.\n\nMathematically, it is represented as <math>\\eta = \\eta_c \\eta_p</math><ref>[http://www.hq.nasa.gov/pao/History/SP-468/ch10-3.htm ch10-3<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100914184628/http://www.hq.nasa.gov/pao/History/SP-468/ch10-3.htm |date=2010-09-14 }}</ref> where <math>\\eta_c</math> is the [[cycle efficiency]] and <math>\\eta_p</math> is the propulsive efficiency. The cycle efficiency, in percent, is the proportion of energy that can be derived from the energy source that is converted to mechanical energy by the [[engine]].\n\n[[File:Propulsive efficiency.png|thumb|right|Dependence of the propulsive efficiency (<math>\\eta_p</math>) upon the vehicle speed/exhaust speed ratio (v/c) for rocket and jet engines]]\n\nFor jet aircraft the ''propulsive efficiency'' (essentially [[Energy conservation|energy efficiency]]) is highest when the engine emits an exhaust jet at a speed that is the same as, or nearly the same as, the vehicle velocity. The exact formula for air-breathing engines as given in the literature,<ref>K.Honicke, R.Lindner, P.Anders, M.Krahl, H.Hadrich, K.Rohricht. Beschreibung der Konstruktion der Triebwerksanlagen. Interflug, Berlin, 1968</ref><ref name=spt>Spittle, Peter. [http://users.encs.concordia.ca/~kadem/Rolls%20Royce.pdf \"Gas turbine technology\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031143409/http://users.encs.concordia.ca/~kadem/Rolls%20Royce.pdf |date=2014-10-31 }} p507, ''[[Rolls-Royce plc]]'', 2003. Retrieved: 21 July 2012.</ref> is\n\n:<math>\\eta_p = \\frac{2}{1 + \\frac{c}{v}}</math>\n\nwhere ''c'' is the exhaust speed, and ''v'' is the speed of the aircraft.\n\n==Range==\n{{main|Range (aircraft)}}\nFor a long range jet operating in the [[stratosphere]], the speed of sound is constant, hence flying at fixed angle of attack and constant [[Mach number]] causes the aircraft to climb, without changing the value of the local speed of sound. In this case:\n\n<math>V=aM</math>\n\nwhere <math>M</math> is the cruise Mach number and <math>a</math> the local speed of sound.   The range equation can be shown to be:\n\n<math>R=\\frac{aM}{c_T}\\frac{C_L}{C_D}ln\\frac{W_1}{W_2}</math>\n\nwhich is known as the ''Breguet range equation'' after the French aviation pioneer [[Louis Charles Breguet]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Coand\u0103-1910]]\n* [[Commercial aviation]]\n* [[Contrail]]\n* [[Jet airliner]]\n* [[Jet noise]]\n* [[Wide-body aircraft|Jumbo jet]]\n* [[Very light jet]]\n* [[List of jet aircraft of World War II]]\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* Lutz Warsitz: ''The First Jet Pilot \u2013 The Story of German Test Pilot Erich Warsitz'', Pen and Sword Books Ltd., England, 2009, {{ISBN|978-1-84415-818-8}}, [http://www.pen-and-sword.co.uk/?product_id=1762 English Edition]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Aircraft with jet engines}}\n* [http://www.erichwarsitz.com The official Erich Warsitz website (the world's first jet pilot), inclusive rare videos (Heinkel He 178) and audio commentaries]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jet Aircraft}}\n[[Category:Jet aircraft| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Aircraft class powered by jet propulsion engines}}\n[[File:Boeing 707-340C, JAT - Yugoslav Airlines AN1046903.jpg|thumb|[[Boeing 707]] of [[Jat Airways|JAT Airways]].]]\n[[File:RAF Eurofighter EF-2000 Typhoon F2 Lofting-1.jpg\n|thumb|[[RAF]] [[Eurofighter Typhoon F2] ]]\n\nA '''jet aircraft''' (or simply '''jet''') is an [[aircraft]] (nearly always a [[fixed-wing aircraft]]) propelled by [[jet engine]]s.\n\nWhereas the engines in [[Propeller (aircraft)|propeller-powered aircraft]] generally achieve their maximum efficiency at much lower speeds and altitudes, jet engines and aircraft achieve maximum efficiency at speeds close to or even well above the [[speed of sound]]. Jet aircraft generally cruise at faster than about [[Mach number|Mach]] 0.8 (609&nbsp;mph, 981&nbsp;km/h or 273&nbsp;m/s) at altitudes around {{convert|10000|-|15000|m|ft}} or more.\n\n[[Frank Whittle]], an [[English people|English]] inventor and [[RAF]] officer, developed the concept of the jet engine in 1928,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwn.org.uk/heritage/people/whittle/biography.html|title=Sir Frank Whittle - Jet Engine Inventor - Born In Coventry|first=Chris Studman for|last=CWN|website=www.cwn.org.uk|accessdate=6 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020155022/http://www.cwn.org.uk/heritage/people/whittle/biography.html|archivedate=20 October 2017}}</ref> and [[Hans von Ohain]] in Germany developed the concept independently in the early 1930s. He wrote in February 1936 to [[Ernst Heinkel]], who led the construction of the world's first [[turbojet]] aircraft and jet plane [[Heinkel He 178]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ohain USAF He 178 page61.jpg|thumb|[[Heinkel He 178]], in August 1939 the world's first aircraft to fly purely on turbojet power]]\n[[File:Caproni foto.jpg|thumb|[[Caproni Campini N1]] in flight]]\n\nAfter the first instance of powered flight, a large number of jet engine factories were suggested. [[Ren\u00e9 Lorin]], Morize, Harris proposed systems for creating a jet efflux.<ref>[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1941/1941%20-%202221.html Jet Propulsion of Aircraft Part III] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105190203/http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1941/1941%20-%202221.html |date=2012-11-05}} G Geoffrey Smith ''Flight'' September 25th 1941</ref> In 1910 the [[Romanian people|Romanian]] inventor [[Henri Coand\u0103]] filed a patent on a jet propulsion system which used piston-engine exhaust gases to add heat to an otherwise pure air stream compressed by rotating fan blades in a duct. It was installed in his [[Coand\u0103-1910]] but this craft probably never flew.\n\nRocket-powered jet aircraft were pioneered in Germany. The first aircraft to fly under rocket power was the [[Lippisch Ente]], in 1928.<ref>[http://www.daviddarling.info/encyclopedia/L/Lippisch_Ente.htm \"Lippisch Ente.\"]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}} ''The Internet Encyclopedia of Science: Experimental Aircraft.'' Retrieved: 26 September 2011.</ref> The Ente had previously been flown as a glider. The next year, in 1929, the [[Opel RAK.1]] became the first purpose-built rocket plane to fly.\n\nThe [[turbojet]] was invented in 1939, independently by [[Frank Whittle]] and later [[Hans von Ohain]]. The first turbojet aircraft to fly was the [[Heinkel He 178]] V1 first [[prototype]] of the [[Nazi Germany|German]] Air Force, the ''[[Luftwaffe]]'', on August 27, 1939 in [[Rostock]] (Germany).<ref>Warsitz, Lutz: [http://www.pen-and-sword.co.uk/?product_id=1762 ''The First Jet Pilot \u2013 The Story of German Test Pilot Erich Warsitz'' (p. 125), Pen and Sword Books Ltd., England, 2009] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100603014802/http://www.pen-and-sword.co.uk/?product_id=1762 |date=2010-06-03}}</ref>\n\nThe first flight of a jet-engined aircraft to come to public attention was the [[Kingdom of Italy|Italian]] [[Caproni Campini N.1]] [[motorjet]] prototype that flew on August 27, 1940.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1941/1941%20-%201950.html|title=''Flight'' 28 August 1941|website=flightglobal.com |accessdate=6 May 2018|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020161845/https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1941/1941%20-%201950.html|archivedate=20 October 2017}}</ref> It was the first jet aircraft recognised by the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration A\u00e9ronautique Internationale]] (at the time the German He 178 program was still kept secret). Campini had proposed the motorjet in 1932.\n\nThe British experimental [[Gloster E.28/39]] first took to the air on May 15, 1941, powered by [[Sir Frank Whittle]]'s turbojet.<ref>[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1949/1949%20-%201789.html? \"No Airscrew Necessary...\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025175115/http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1949/1949%20-%201789.html |date=2012-10-25 }} ''Flight''(flightglobal.com), 27 October 1949 p554</ref> The [[United States]] produced the [[Bell P-59 Airacomet|Bell XP-59A]] using two examples of a version of the Whittle engine built by [[General Electric]], which flew on October 1, 1942. The Meteor was the first production jet as it entered production a few months before the Me 262,{{Citation needed|date=March 2016}} which itself had been in development since before the start of the war as Projekt 1065.\n\n[[File:Me 262 flight show at ILA 2006.jpg|thumb|left|A modern reproduction of the Me 262 in flight in 2006. The first operational turbojet aircraft, the Messerschmitt Me 262 entered service in April 1944.]]\n\nThe first operational [[fighter aircraft|jet fighter]] was the [[Messerschmitt Me 262]],<ref>Hecht, Heinrich. ''The World's First Turbojet Fighter \u2013 Messerschmitt Me 262''. Atglen, Pennsylvania: Schiffer Publishing, 1990. {{ISBN|0-88740-234-8}}.{{Page needed|date=October 2010}}</ref> manufactured by Germany during World War II, which entered service on 19 April 1944 with Erprobungskommando 262 at Lechfeld just south of Augsburg. It was the fastest conventional aircraft of [[World War II]]&nbsp;\u2013 although there were faster aircraft propelled by unconventional means, such as the rocket-powered [[Messerschmitt Me 163 Komet]]. The [[Messerschmitt Me 262]] had first flown on April 18, 1941, with initial plans drawn up by Dr Waldemar Voigt's design team in April 1939, but mass production did not start until early 1944 with the first squadrons operational that year, too late for a decisive effect on the outcome of the war.\n\n[[File:Gloster Meteor III ExCC.jpg|thumb|right|Gloster Meteor F.3s. The [[Gloster Meteor]] was the first British jet fighter and the [[Allies of World War II|Allies']] only jet aircraft to achieve combat operations during World War II.]]\n\nAround this time, mid 1944, the United Kingdom's [[Gloster Meteor]] was being committed to defence of the UK against the [[V-1 flying bomb]]&nbsp;\u2013 itself a [[pulsejet]]-powered aircraft&nbsp;and direct ancestor of the [[cruise missile]]\u2013 and then ground-attack operations over Europe in the last months of the war. In 1944 Germany introduced into service the [[Arado Ar 234]] jet reconnaissance and bomber, though chiefly used in the former role, with the [[Heinkel He 162]] ''Spatz'' single-jet [[light fighter]]  premiering as 1944 ended. USSR tested its own [[Bereznyak-Isayev BI-1]] in 1942, but the project was scrapped by [[Joseph Stalin]] in 1945. The [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] also developed jet aircraft in 1945, including the [[Nakajima Kikka|Nakajima J9Y Kikka]], a modified, and slightly smaller version of the Me 262 that had folding wings. By the end of 1945, the US had introduced their first jet fighter, the [[Lockheed P-80 Shooting Star]] into service and the UK its second fighter design, the [[de Havilland Vampire]].\n\n[[File:Lufthansa B737-330 (D-ABXS) approaching London Heathrow Airport.jpg|thumb|left|The Boeing 737-300, part of the [[Boeing 737]] family is the most produced jet aircraft that is still operating.]]\n\nThe US introduced the [[North American B-45 Tornado]], their first jet bomber, into service in 1948. Although capable of carrying nuclear weapons it was used for reconnaissance over Korea. On November 8, 1950, during the [[Korean War]], [[United States Air Force]] Lt. Russell J. Brown, flying in an [[P-80 Shooting Star|F-80]], intercepted two [[North Korea]]n [[MiG-15]]s near the [[Yalu River]] and shot them down in the first jet-to-jet [[dogfight]] in history. The UK put the [[English Electric Canberra]] into service in 1951 as a [[light bomber]]. It was designed to fly higher and faster than any [[Interceptor aircraft|interceptor]].\n\n[[File:BOAC Comet 1952 Entebbe.jpg|thumb|[[British Overseas Airways Corporation|BOAC]] Comet 1 was the first passenger jet airliner]]\n[[File:Boeing 707-138B Qantas Jett Clipper Ella N707JT.jpg|thumb|Boeing 707]]\n\n[[BOAC]] operated the first commercial jet service, from [[London]] to [[Johannesburg]], in 1952 with the [[de Havilland Comet]] [[jet airliner|jetliner]]. This highly innovative aircraft travelled far faster and higher than the propeller aircraft, was much quieter, smoother, and had stylish blended wings containing hidden jet engines. However, due to a design defect, and use of aluminium alloys, the aircraft suffered catastrophic [[metal fatigue]] which led to several crashes.<ref name=\"ruled\">Jet! When Britain Ruled the Skies - BBC</ref>\n\nThe series of crashes gave time for the [[Boeing 707]] to enter service in 1958 and this came to dominate the market for civilian airliners. The underslung engines were found to be advantageous in the event of a propellant leak, and so the 707 looked rather different from the Comet: the 707 has a shape that is effectively the same as that of contemporary aircraft, with marked commonality still evident today for example with the [[Boeing 737|737]] (fuselage) and [[Airbus A340|A340]] (single deck, swept wing, four below-wing engines).\n\n[[Turbofan]] aircraft began entering service in the 1950s and 1960s, bringing far greater [[fuel efficiency]], and this is the type of jet in widespread use today.\n[[File:Tu-144LL_in_flight.jpg|thumb|[[Tu-144]],  the world's first commercial [[supersonic transport]] aircraft (SST) ]]\n\nThe [[Tu-144]] [[supersonic transport]] was the fastest commercial jet plane at Mach 2.35 (1,555&nbsp;mph, 2,503&nbsp;km/h). It went into service in 1975, but soon stopped flying. The Mach 2 [[Concorde]] aircraft entered service in 1976 and flew for 27 years.\n\nThe fastest military jet plane was the [[SR-71 Blackbird]] at Mach 3.35 (2,275&nbsp;mph, 3,661&nbsp;km/h).\n\n==Other jets==\nMost people use the term 'jet aircraft' to denote gas turbine based [[airbreathing jet engine]]s, but rockets and scramjets are both also propelled by jet propulsion.\n\n[[Cruise missile]]s are single-use unmanned jet aircraft, powered predominately by ramjets or turbojets or sometimes turbofans, but they will often have a rocket propulsion system for initial propulsion.\n\nThe fastest airbreathing jet aircraft is the unmanned [[NASA X-43|X-43]] scramjet at around Mach 9\u201310.\n\nThe fastest manned (rocket) aircraft is the [[X-15]] at Mach 6.85.\n\nThe [[Space Shuttle]], while far faster than the X-43 or X-15, was not regarded as an aircraft during ascent as it was carried [[ballistics|ballistically]] by rocket thrust, rather than the air. During re-entry it was classed (like a glider) as an unpowered aircraft. The first flight was in 1981.\n\nThe [[Bell 533]] (1964), [[Lockheed XH-51]] (1965), and [[Sikorsky S-69]] (1977-1981) are examples of [[compound helicopter]] designs where jet exhaust added to forward thrust.<ref name=ieee>{{cite web|url= https://spectrum.ieee.org/aerospace/aviation/the-fastest-helicopter-on-earth |title=The Fastest Helicopter on Earth |authors=Thomas Lawrence and David Jenney|publisher=[[IEEE Spectrum]] |date=31 Aug 2010|accessdate=1 August 2017 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170130223834/https://spectrum.ieee.org/aerospace/aviation/the-fastest-helicopter-on-earth |archivedate=30 January 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Hiller YH-32 Hornet]] and [[Fairey Ultra-light Helicopter]] were among the many helicopters where the rotors were driven by [[tip jet]]s.\n\nJet-powered [[Wingsuit flying|wingsuits]] exist - powered by model aircraft jet engines - but of short duration and needing to be launched at height.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2013/07/how-to-fly-like-jetman/|title=\u2018Jetman\u2019 Yves Rossy Shows Us How to Fly His Carbon Fiber Jet Wing|publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=31 July 2013 |accessdate=1 August 2017 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170102151845/https://www.wired.com/2013/07/how-to-fly-like-jetman/ |archivedate=2 January 2017 |url-status= live  }}</ref>\n\n==Aerodynamics==\n[[File:McDonnell Douglas DC-10-30(ER), Biman Bangladesh AN0547320.jpg|thumb|A [[McDonnell Douglas DC-10]], an example of a [[Trijet]] configuration]]\nBecause of the way they work, the typical exhaust speed of jet engines is transonic or faster, therefore most jet aircraft need to fly at high speeds, either [[supersonic]] or speeds just below the speed of sound (\"[[transonic]]\") so as to achieve efficient flight. Aerodynamics is therefore an important consideration.\n\nJet aircraft are usually designed using the [[Whitcomb area rule]], which says that the total area of cross-section of the aircraft at any point along the aircraft from the nose must be approximately the same as that of a [[Sears-Haack body]]. A shape with that property minimises the production of shockwaves which would waste energy.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Jet engines==\n{{Main|Jet engine}}\n\nJet engines come in several main types:\n*[[turbojet]]\n*[[turbofan]] (which come in two main forms [[low bypass turbofan]] and [[high bypass turbofan]])\n*[[rocket]]\n\nThe different types are used for different purposes.\n\nRockets are the oldest type and are mainly used when extremely high speeds or extremely high altitudes are needed. Due to the extreme, typically [[hypersonic]], exhaust velocity and the necessity of oxidiser being carried on board, they consume propellant extremely quickly. For this reason, they are not practical for routine transportation.\n\nTurbojets are the second oldest type; it has a high, usually supersonic, exhaust speed and low frontal cross-section, and so is best suited to high-speed, usually supersonic, flight. Although once widely used, they are relatively inefficient compared to [[turboprop]] and turbofans for subsonic flight. The last major aircraft to use turbojets were Concorde and Tu-144 [[supersonic transport]]s.\n\nLow bypass turbofans have a lower exhaust speed than turbojets and are mostly used for high sonic, transonic, and low supersonic speeds. High bypass turbofans are used for subsonic aircraft and are quite efficient and are widely used for airliners.\n\n==Flying characteristics==\nJet aircraft fly considerably differently to propeller aircraft.\n\nOne difference is that jet engines respond relatively slowly. This complicates takeoff and landing maneuvers.\nIn particular, during takeoff, propeller aircraft engines blow air over their wings and that gives more lift and a shorter takeoff. These differences caught out some early BOAC Comet pilots.<ref name=ruled/>\n\n==Propulsive efficiency==\n{{main|Propulsive efficiency}}\nIn aircraft ''overall propulsive efficiency'' <math>\\eta</math> is the efficiency, in percent, with which the energy contained in a vehicle's propellant is converted into useful energy, to replace losses due to [[air drag]], gravity, and acceleration. It can also be stated as the proportion of the mechanical energy actually used to propel the aircraft. It is always less than 100% because of kinetic energy loss to the exhaust, and less-than-ideal efficiency of the propulsive mechanism, whether a [[Propeller (aircraft)|propeller]], a jet exhaust, or a fan. In addition, propulsive efficiency is greatly dependent on [[air density]] and airspeed.\n\nMathematically, it is represented as <math>\\eta = \\eta_c \\eta_p</math><ref>[http://www.hq.nasa.gov/pao/History/SP-468/ch10-3.htm ch10-3<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100914184628/http://www.hq.nasa.gov/pao/History/SP-468/ch10-3.htm |date=2010-09-14 }}</ref> where <math>\\eta_c</math> is the [[cycle efficiency]] and <math>\\eta_p</math> is the propulsive efficiency. The cycle efficiency, in percent, is the proportion of energy that can be derived from the energy source that is converted to mechanical energy by the [[engine]].\n\n[[File:Propulsive efficiency.png|thumb|right|Dependence of the propulsive efficiency (<math>\\eta_p</math>) upon the vehicle speed/exhaust speed ratio (v/c) for rocket and jet engines]]\n\nFor jet aircraft the ''propulsive efficiency'' (essentially [[Energy conservation|energy efficiency]]) is highest when the engine emits an exhaust jet at a speed that is the same as, or nearly the same as, the vehicle velocity. The exact formula for air-breathing engines as given in the literature,<ref>K.Honicke, R.Lindner, P.Anders, M.Krahl, H.Hadrich, K.Rohricht. Beschreibung der Konstruktion der Triebwerksanlagen. Interflug, Berlin, 1968</ref><ref name=spt>Spittle, Peter. [http://users.encs.concordia.ca/~kadem/Rolls%20Royce.pdf \"Gas turbine technology\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031143409/http://users.encs.concordia.ca/~kadem/Rolls%20Royce.pdf |date=2014-10-31 }} p507, ''[[Rolls-Royce plc]]'', 2003. Retrieved: 21 July 2012.</ref> is\n\n:<math>\\eta_p = \\frac{2}{1 + \\frac{c}{v}}</math>\n\nwhere ''c'' is the exhaust speed, and ''v'' is the speed of the aircraft.\n\n==Range==\n{{main|Range (aircraft)}}\nFor a long range jet operating in the [[stratosphere]], the speed of sound is constant, hence flying at fixed angle of attack and constant [[Mach number]] causes the aircraft to climb, without changing the value of the local speed of sound. In this case:\n\n<math>V=aM</math>\n\nwhere <math>M</math> is the cruise Mach number and <math>a</math> the local speed of sound.   The range equation can be shown to be:\n\n<math>R=\\frac{aM}{c_T}\\frac{C_L}{C_D}ln\\frac{W_1}{W_2}</math>\n\nwhich is known as the ''Breguet range equation'' after the French aviation pioneer [[Louis Charles Breguet]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Coand\u0103-1910]]\n* [[Commercial aviation]]\n* [[Contrail]]\n* [[Jet airliner]]\n* [[Jet noise]]\n* [[Wide-body aircraft|Jumbo jet]]\n* [[Very light jet]]\n* [[List of jet aircraft of World War II]]\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* Lutz Warsitz: ''The First Jet Pilot \u2013 The Story of German Test Pilot Erich Warsitz'', Pen and Sword Books Ltd., England, 2009, {{ISBN|978-1-84415-818-8}}, [http://www.pen-and-sword.co.uk/?product_id=1762 English Edition]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Aircraft with jet engines}}\n* [http://www.erichwarsitz.com The official Erich Warsitz website (the world's first jet pilot), inclusive rare videos (Heinkel He 178) and audio commentaries]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jet Aircraft}}\n[[Category:Jet aircraft| ]]\n", "name_user": "46.102.39.84", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jet_aircraft"}
{"title_page": "John Sentamu", "text_new": "{{short description|Archbishop of York}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| honorific-prefix = {{pre-nominal styles|size=100%|MRevd|&RHPC}}\n| name = John Sentamu\n| honorific-suffix = <!---------- Please do not fill in here academic degrees according WP:MOSBIO ---------->\n| title = [[Archbishop of York]]<br />and [[Canterbury\u2013York dispute|Primate of England]]\n| image = Official portrait of The Lord Archbishop of York crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Sentamu in 2019\n| province = [[Province of York|York]]\n| diocese = [[Diocese of York|York]]\n| enthroned = 30 November 2005<ref name=\"enth\">{{cite news |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/north_yorkshire/4481796.stm | title = First black Archbishop enthroned | date = 30 November 2005 |work=BBC News  | accessdate =12 August 2006 }}</ref>\n| predecessor = [[David Hope, Baron Hope of Thornes|David Hope]]\n| ordination = 1979\n| consecration = 25 September 1996\n| consecrated_by = [[George Carey]]\n| other_post = [[Bishop of Stepney]] (1996\u20132002)<br />[[Bishop of Birmingham]] (2002\u20132005)\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name = John Tucker Mugabi Sentamu\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1949|6|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Kampala]], Uganda\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]<!-- As a matter of course and reasonable expectation: Wholly unreasonable (and malicious) to suspect that the Archbishop of York of the Church of England (\"Established Church\" in England) has not legally and formally acquired British nationality and British citizenship (likely) by a procedure called \"naturalisation\" or by some other means (made a British citizen by the Home Office, for and on behalf of the Secretary of State (Home Secretary)) some point during his life (probably long) before becoming Archbishop. -->\n| religion = [[Church of England]]\n| residence = [[Bishopthorpe Palace]], [[Bishopthorpe]], [[York]]\n| parents = John and Ruth Walakira<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2006-Ra-Z/Sentamu-John.html |title=Notable Biography |publisher=Notablebiographies.com |accessdate=30 April 2011}}</ref>\n| spouse = {{marriage|Margaret|1973}}\n| children = Two<ref name=bbckids>{{cite web|last1=Holmes|first1=Tara|title=Breaking the mould|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/christianity/people/johnsentamu_1.shtml|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=21 November 2014}}</ref>\n| profession = Cleric, lawyer\n| alma_mater = {{unbulleted list | [[Makerere University]] | [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]] | [[Ridley Hall, Cambridge]]}}\n| module        = {{Infobox officeholder | embed = yes\n |office         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br /><small>[[Lords Spiritual|Lord Spiritual]]</small>\n|term_start = 25 January 2006\n|term_end       =}}\n}}\n'''John Tucker Mugabi Sentamu''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|\u025b|n|t|\u0259m|u\u02d0}};<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phonetic-blog.blogspot.de/2012/10/an-archiepiscopal-mnemonic.html |title=an archiepiscopal mnemonic  |accessdate=10 October 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303235800/http://phonetic-blog.blogspot.de/2012/10/an-archiepiscopal-mnemonic.html |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref> {{IPA-lg|s\u02d0\u00e9\u02d0nt\u00e1m\u00fb|Luganda:}}; born 10 June 1949) is an Anglican bishop, serving as the 97th [[Archbishop of York]], [[Metropolitan (religion)|Metropolitan]] of [[Province of York|York]], and [[primate (bishop)|Primate]] of England. The position of Archbishop of York is the second most senior clerical position in the [[Church of England]] after that of the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], Primate of All England.\n\nBorn near [[Kampala]] in [[Uganda]], Sentamu studied law at [[Makerere University]] before gaining employment as an [[barrister|advocate]] of the [[Supreme Court of Uganda]]. Speaking out against the regime of President [[Idi Amin]], he was briefly imprisoned before fleeing in 1974 to the United Kingdom, where he devoted himself to [[Anglicanism]], beginning his study of [[theology]] at [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]], in 1976 and eventually gaining a doctorate in 1984. He studied for ordination at [[Ridley Hall, Cambridge]], and was ordained in 1979. In 1996 he was consecrated as the [[area bishop|area]] [[Bishop of Stepney]] and in 2002 moved to the position of [[Bishop of Birmingham]]. In 2005 he was appointed to the position of [[Archbishop of York]].\n\nSentamu expresses support for some traditionalist positions within the [[Church of England]], as he has publicly criticised [[multiculturalism]] and the legalisation of [[same-sex marriage]], but contrary to traditional Christian moral teaching he supports [[cohabitation]] before marriage, stating \"We are living at a time where some people ... want to test whether the milk is good before they buy the cow.\"<ref name=marriage>{{cite news|title=Archbishop backs William and Kate's decision to live together before marriage|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/royal-wedding/8481736/Royal-wedding-Archbishop-backs-William-and-Kates-decision-to-live-together-before-marriage.html|accessdate=3 April 2013|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=29 April 2011}}</ref> He has also received attention for his vocal criticism of former Zimbabwean president [[Robert Mugabe]].\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nSentamu was born in 1949 in a village near [[Kampala]], [[Uganda Protectorate|Uganda]], the sixth of thirteen children. He obtained a [[Bachelor of Laws]] at [[Makerere University]], [[Kampala]], and practised as an [[barrister|advocate]] of the High Court of Uganda until 1974, being briefly a judge of the High Court. In 1973, he married his wife Margaret.<ref name=vallely>{{cite news|last1=Vallely|first1=Paul|title=Dr John Sentamu: Next stop Canterbury?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/dr-john-sentamu-next-stop-canterbury-7624760.html|accessdate=21 November 2014|work=[[The Independent]]|date=7 April 2012}}</ref> Three weeks after his marriage, he incurred the wrath of the dictator [[Idi Amin]] and was detained for 90 days. In a speech in 2007, he described how during that time he had been \"kicked around like a football and beaten terribly\", saying \"the temptation to give up hope of release was always present\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.24dash.com/communities/20416.htm |title=''Archbishop tells his captivity story in call to free Alan Johnson'' |accessdate=20 November 2007 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926234859/http://www.24dash.com/communities/20416.htm |archivedate=26 September 2007 }}, 24dash.com. Retrieved 11 January 2009</ref> He fled his home country to arrive as an [[Immigration|immigrant]] in the [[United Kingdom]] in 1974.\n\n===Education and early ministry===\nSentamu studied theology at [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]] (Bachelor of Arts {BA} 1976, [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|Cambridge Master of Arts]] {MA Cantab} 1979, [[Doctor of Philosophy]] {PhD} 1984). He was baptized at Eden Baptist Church, Cambridge. He trained for the priesthood at [[Ridley Hall, Cambridge]], being ordained a priest in 1979. His doctoral thesis is entitled \"Some aspects of [[soteriology]], with particular reference to the thought of [[J. K. Mozley]], from an African perspective\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ulmss-newton.lib.cam.ac.uk/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?SC=Author&SA=Sentamu%2C%20John |title=University of Cambridge library catalogue |access-date=5 December 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003085608/https://ulmss-newton.lib.cam.ac.uk/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?SC=Author&SA=Sentamu%2C%20John |archive-date=3 October 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He worked as assistant chaplain at Selwyn College, as chaplain at a remand centre and as [[curate]] and [[vicar]] in a series of parish appointments.\n\nSentamu was [[consecrated]] a bishop on 25 September 1996, by [[George Carey]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], at [[St Paul's Cathedral]];<ref>{{Church Times | title = London welcomes bishops | archive = 1996_09_27_001 | issue = 6972 | date = 27 September 1996 | page = 1 | accessed = 26 June 2018 }}</ref> to serve as [[Bishop of Stepney]], a [[suffragan bishop|suffragan]] and [[area bishop]] in the [[Diocese of London]]. It was during this time that he served as advisor to the [[Stephen Lawrence]] Judicial Enquiry. In 2002 he chaired the [[Damilola Taylor]] review. That same year he was appointed [[Bishop of Birmingham]] where his ministry, according to the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[Rowan Williams]], was praised by \"Christians of all backgrounds\".{{citation needed|date=June 2012}} Sentamu became President of Youth for Christ in 2004 and President of the YMCA in April 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.archbishopofyork.org/780 |title=Biography |publisher=The Archbishop of York |accessdate=30 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722104742/http://www.archbishopofyork.org/780 |archive-date=22 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Archbishop of York===\nOn 17 June 2005 the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|prime minister's]] office announced Sentamu's translation to [[Diocese of York|York]] as the 97th archbishop.<ref name=\"appt\">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/4102582.stm | title = New Archbishop of York appointed |date =17 June 2005 |work=BBC News  | accessdate =12 August 2006 }}</ref> He was formally elected by the chapter of [[York Minster]] on 21 July,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=57706 |page=9331|date=19 July 2005}}</ref> legally confirmed as archbishop at [[St Mary-le-Bow]], London on 5 October,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140201190444/http://www.churchofengland.org/media-centre/news/2005/10/pr7305a.aspx Church of England \u2013 Sentamu: Confirmation as Archbishop of York] (Accessed 15 July 2013)</ref> and enthroned at York Minster on 30 November 2005 (the feast of [[Saint Andrew]]), at a ceremony with African singing and dancing and contemporary music, with Sentamu himself playing African drums during the service.<ref name=\"enth\" /><ref>{{cite news | url = http://politics.guardian.co.uk/homeaffairs/story/0,11026,1508879,00.html | title = First black Church of England archbishop appointed | date = 17 June 2005 | work=The Guardian | accessdate =12 August 2006 | location=London | first=Simon | last=Jeffery}}</ref> As Archbishop of York, Sentamu sits in the [[House of Lords]]<ref>[https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/archbishop_of_york They Work For You] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420231715/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/archbishop_of_york |date=20 April 2016 }}</ref> and was admitted, as a matter of course, to the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"deb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/search/results/19338/John%20Tucker%20Mugabi%20Sentamu+YORK.aspx |title=Debrett's People of Today \u2013 John Sentamu York |publisher=Debretts.com |date=6 October 1949 |accessdate=30 April 2011}}</ref> He was the first black archbishop in the Church of England.<ref name=\"enth\" /><ref name=\"appt\" />\n\n[[File:York Easter Sunday 2007.jpg|thumb|250px|left|John Sentamu outside York Minster on [[Easter Sunday]], 2007.]] \nFor a week in August 2006, Sentamu camped in York Minster, forgoing food in solidarity with those affected by the Middle East conflict, especially the children and other civilians killed and injured during the [[2006 Lebanon War]], when [[cluster bombs]] were used by Israeli forces.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/world/2006/0812/1155291283803.html | title = Anglican archbishop's solidarity fast | date = 12 August 2006 | work=The Irish Times | accessdate =12 August 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/help/3681938.stm |title=John Sentamu to fast |date=12 August 2006 |work=BBC News |accessdate=14 August 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060813215404/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/help/3681938.stm |archivedate=13 August 2006 }}<!-- BBC Video and Audio help page --></ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/g2/story/0,,1851757,00.html | title = Inside is a strange place to pitch a tent\u2026 | date = 17 August 2006 |work=The Guardian |location=UK | accessdate =17 August 2006  | first=Stephen | last=Bates}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 March 2007, Sentamu was installed as the first Chancellor of [[York St John University]]. On 1 June 2007 he was appointed as the first Chancellor of the [[University of Cumbria]]. He took up the position when the university opened on 1 August 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Archbishop becomes new chancellor|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/6711449.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=6 December 2011|date=1 June 2007}}</ref> In July 2009, he was awarded an honorary doctorate by [[University of Chester]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chester.ac.uk/node/6184 |title=Twelve of the University of Chester\u2019s recent triumphs |publisher=Chester.ac.uk |date=13 July 2010 |accessdate=29 November 2011}}</ref> On 15 July 2010, Sentamu was presented with an honorary degree from the [[University of York]] by the Provost of Vanbrugh College, [[David Efird]] of the Department of Philosophy,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-10656063 |work=BBC News  | title=Archbishop John Sentamu receives an honorary degree | date=15 July 2010}}</ref> and on 16 July 2010 was presented with an honorary degree from the [[University of Leeds]] by the chancellor of the university, [[Melvyn Bragg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leeds.ac.uk/info/30310/honorary_graduates/305/john_sentamu |title=John Sentamu \u2013 John Sentamu \u2013 University of Leeds |publisher=Leeds.ac.uk |date=16 July 2010 |accessdate=30 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608141223/http://www.leeds.ac.uk/info/30310/honorary_graduates/305/john_sentamu |archivedate= 8 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 July 2007, Sentamu was presented with an honorary degree from the [[University of Hull]] by the chancellor of the university, [[Virginia Bottomley]], at [[Hull City Hall]] during the graduation ceremony for graduands of the Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences.<ref>[http://www.hull.ac.uk/news/july07/archyork.html The University of Hull] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417131925/http://www.hull.ac.uk/news/july07/archyork.html |date=17 April 2009 }}</ref> On 19 July 2007 he was presented with an honorary degree (Doctor of Letters) from the [[University of Sheffield]] in recognition of his distinguished career as a scholar and theologian.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.shef.ac.uk/mediacentre/archbishop.html | title = Archbishop of York awarded honorary degree | date = 23 July 2007 | publisher=University of Sheffield | accessdate =23 July 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2007 Sentamu was awarded the \"Yorkshireman of the Year\" title by the [[Black Sheep Brewery]]. In his acceptance speech he praised the welcome he had received from the people of [[Yorkshire]] and made reference to the \"[[Haplogroup A (Y-DNA)#A1-P108|African-Yorkshire DNA connection]]\", joking that perhaps his parents had this in mind when they gave him the name \"Mugabi\", which, spelled backwards, is \"Ibagum\" (\"ee-by-gum\", a stock phrase popularly supposed to be used to express shock or disbelief in northern England).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dioceseofyork.org.uk/cgi/news/news.cgi?t=template&a=1186 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416063556/http://www.dioceseofyork.org.uk/cgi/news/news.cgi?t=template&a=1186 |url-status=dead |archivedate=16 April 2009 |title=Speech by the Most Revd & Rt Hon Dr John Sentamu on accepting the Yorkshire Man of the Year Award |date=26 October 2007 |publisher=The Diocese of York |accessdate=30 November 2007 }}</ref> In 2008 Archbishop [[Thurstan]] Church of England School in Hull was renamed [[Archbishop Sentamu Academy]] in his honour.\n\nIn October 2018, Sentamu announced his retirement, scheduled for 7 June 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Archbishop of York Dr John Sentamu to retire |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-45707419 |website=BBC News |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> In June 2019, he ordained his wife as a deacon.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Vicky |date=23 June 2019 |title=Archbishop of York to ordain new deacons - including his wife - at York Minster |url=https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/17722183.archbishop-of-york-to-ordain-new-deacons-including-his-wife-at-york-minster/ |work=[[The Press (York)|The Press]]|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nSentamu has spoken on issues including young people, the family, slavery, and injustice and conflict abroad.  In an early TV appearance in 1988 he joined, among others, [[Ray Honeyford]], [[Ann Dummett]] and [[Lurline Champagnie]] to discuss \"Race and the classroom\" on ''[[After Dark (TV series)|After Dark]]''.<ref>[[List of After Dark editions]], accessed 20 September 2012</ref> In November 2005 he sought re-discovery of English pride and cultural identity, stating that zeal for [[multiculturalism]] had sometimes \"seemed to imply, wrongly for me, 'let other cultures be allowed to express themselves but do not let the majority culture at all tell us its glories, its struggles, its joys, its pains'.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2-1882591,00.html | title = Multiculturalism has betrayed the English, Archbishop says | date = 30 November 2005 |work=The Times |location=UK | accessdate =12 August 2006 | first=Ruth | last=Gledhill |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060513154744/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2-1882591,00.html|archive-date=13 May 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> \nIn 2006 he claimed that the [[BBC]] was frightened of criticising [[Islam]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2006/11/14/nmuslim14.xml|accessdate=24 March 2007|date=15 November 2006|title=BBC frightened of criticising Islam, says archbishop|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|first=Jonathan|last=Petre|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061114195539/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=%2Fnews%2F2006%2F11%2F14%2Fnmuslim14.xml|archive-date=14 November 2006|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Sentamu featured prominently in the British press because of his comments on the treatment of detainees in [[Guantanamo Bay Naval Base]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.independent.co.uk/world/americas/article346214.ece|title=The Americans are breaking international law...|date=18 February 2006|work=The Independent|location=UK|accessdate=30 November 2006|first1=Ian|last1=Herbert|first2=Ben|last2=Russell|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070106161441/http://news.independent.co.uk/world/americas/article346214.ece|archivedate=6 January 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Poverty===\nSentamu regrets that many low paid workers are not paid enough to lift them and their families out of [[poverty]]. \n{{quote|The issue  is one that strikes to the heart of the moral fabric of our society. For the very first time the majority of households in poverty in Britain have at least one person working. The nature of poverty in Britain is changing dramatically. For millions of hard-pressed people, work is no longer a route out of poverty. (...) Low pay is a scourge on our society, and we all pay for it. Low pay costs the taxpayer between 3.6 and 6 billion pounds a year in tax credits, in-work benefits and lost tax receipts. And as disposable income available to the lowest paid reduces, so too does the demand in the economy.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/dr-john-sentamu-for-millions-of-people-work-is-no-longer-a-way-out-of-poverty-9117824.html Dr John Sentamu: For millions of people, work is no longer a way out of poverty]</ref>}}\n\n{{quote|Once upon a time you couldn't really be living in poverty if you had a regular income, you could find yourself on a low income, yes. But that is not longer so. You can be in work and still live in poverty.<ref name=\"Guradian19/11/13\">[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/nov/19/food-poverty-archbishop-york-john-sentamu Archbishop attacks UK food poverty]</ref>}}\n\nSentamu believes that food poverty is causing [[malnutrition]] in the UK.  In 2013, he said that \"last year more than 27,000 people were diagnosed as suffering from malnutrition in Leeds \u2013 not Lesotho, not Liberia, not Lusaka but Leeds?\" and feels these reports \"disgrace us all, leaving a dark stain on our consciences\".<ref name=\"Guradian19/11/13\" /> Government welfare reform were, \n{{quote|beginning to bite \u2013 with reductions in housing benefit for so-called under-occupation of social housing, the cap on benefits for workless householders and single parents, and the gradual replacement of the disability living allowance with a personal independence payment\".<ref name=\"Guradian19/11/13\"/>}}\n\n===General election===\nIn the run up to the [[2017 United Kingdom general election]] [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[Justin Welby]] and John Sentamu campaigned over the need to address [[Poverty in the United Kingdom#Poverty in the UK in the 21st century|poverty]], [[Education in the United Kingdom|education]], housing and [[National Health Service|health]].  The archbishops stressed the importance of \"education for all, of urgent and serious solutions to our housing challenges, the importance of creating communities as well as In the run up to the [[2017 United Kingdom general election]], and a confident and flourishing health service that gives support to all - especially the vulnerable - not least at the beginning and end of life.\"<ref>[http://www.itv.com/news/2017-05-06/archbishops-of-canterbury-and-york-raise-election-concerns-in-letter/ Archbishops of Canterbury and York raise election concerns in letter]</ref>\n\n===Stop and search===\nIn 2000, Sentamu, then [[Bishop of Stepney]], was stopped by a [[City of London Police]] officer near [[St Paul's Cathedral]].  Sentamu claimed it was the eighth time he had been questioned by police in eight years, and that he was the only Church of England bishop to have been stopped by police in this way.<ref name=guardian-Jan-2000>{{cite news|last=Dodd|first=Vikram|title=Black bishop 'demeaned' by police search|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2000/jan/24/race.world|accessdate=27 September 2011|newspaper=The Guardian|date=24 January 2000|location=London}}</ref> In a 2010 debate in the [[House of Lords]], Sentamu was critical of the standards of \"reasonable grounds to suspect\" applied by police.<ref name=hansard-1278>{{cite web|title=Volume No. 720 - 27 July 2010 : Column 1278|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201011/ldhansrd/text/100727-0002.htm#10072739000568|work=Hansard|publisher=Houses of Parliament|accessdate=27 September 2011|date=27 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===\"Chocolate Trinity\" comments===\nOne of Sentamu's favourite references is to \"The Chocolate Trinity\" of God-fearing [[Quaker]] capitalists who were involved in developing the chocolate industry:<ref name=\"Lecture notes\">[http://www.dioceseofyork.org.uk/cgi/news/news.cgi?t=template&a=908 Bishop\u2019s lecture notes on York Diocese website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416072157/http://www.dioceseofyork.org.uk/cgi/news/news.cgi?t=template&a=908 |date=16 April 2009 }}.</ref><ref name = \"Ebor\">His [[Ebor Lecture]] in [[York Minster]] (13 September 2006).</ref>\n\n* [[George Cadbury]]: \"More than just a sweet man\"\n* [[Joseph Rowntree (Philanthropist)|Joseph Rowntree]]:  \"an adventurer to the end of life, forever peering forward, never content with what had been achieved.\"\n* [[Joseph Storrs Fry II]] (J. S. Fry):  \"the very model of the pre-1860 Quaker, with his [[plain dress]] a relic of the past and a reflection of his narrow conservative approach to both religion and business.\"\n\n===Robert Mugabe===\n[[Image:John Sentamu York City v. AFC Telford United 1.png|thumb|right|Sentamu wearing a clerical shirt without its white insert, 2009]]\nOn 9 December 2007, during a live television interview with [[Andrew Marr]] on [[BBC One]], Sentamu made a protest against [[Zimbabwe]]an president [[Robert Mugabe]]. Sentamu took the white insert off his [[clerical collar|clerical shirt]] and cut it up stating that: {{quote |as an Anglican, this is what I wear to identify myself that I'm a clergyman. Do you know what Mugabe has done? He's taken people's identity and literally if you don't mind, cut it to pieces. This is what he's actually done, to a lot of\u2014and in the end there's nothing. So as far as I'm concerned from now on I'm not going to wear a dog collar until Mugabe's gone.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7135087.stm |title=Archbishop makes Zimbabwe protest |accessdate=9 December 2007 |work=BBC News  | date=9 December 2007}}</ref>}}His protest followed criticism against Mugabe at the EU-Africa summit in [[Lisbon]].\n\nIn December 2008, Sentamu again spoke out against Mugabe, saying \"The time has come for Robert Mugabe to answer for his crimes against humanity, against his countrymen and women and for justice to be done\".<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7769546.stm\n|title = Archbishop urges Mugabe overthrow.\n|accessdate =6 December 2008\n|date = 6 December 2008\n|work=BBC News \n}}\n</ref>\n\nOn 26 November 2017, Sentamu returned to ''The Andrew Marr Show'' and kept his promise to reinstate his dog collar following Robert Mugabe's resignation earlier in the week.\n\nMarr presented him with an envelope containing the original cut up pieces of collar. Of it he said \n{{quote |You know, Andrew, I could attempt to put this one back together using superglue, but it would be a pretty ropey collar. And I actually think the lesson for Zimbabwe is the same. They just can't try and stitch it up. Something more radical, something new needs to happen.</small><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-42128073|title=Archbishop ends 10-year Mugabe protest|date=2017-11-26|work=BBC News|accessdate=2017-11-26}}</ref>}}\n\nHe then put on a new dog collar which he had brought with him. He also said it could be possible for Zimbabweans to forgive Mr Mugabe. \"Mugabe needs to say at some point to Zimbabweans: 'Forgive me'. He's a very, very intelligent man and I think he is capable of doing it.\"\n\n===Financial crisis===\nIn September 2008, Sentamu and the Archbishop of Canterbury, [[Rowan Williams]], spoke out against opportunistic stock market trading. Sentamu compared those who practised [[short selling]] of [[HBOS]] shares, driving the share prices down, to \"bank robbers\".<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7634641.stm\n|title = Archbishops attack City practices\n|accessdate =25 September 2008\n|date = 25 September 2008\n|work=BBC News \n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Sexuality and marriage===\n[[File:Archbishop of York, Rev Grace Sentamu-Baverstock (28449165817) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Sentamu and his daughter Grace Sentamu-Baverstock]]\nSentamu, born in Uganda, said [[Uganda Anti-Homosexuality Bill|laws being debated in Uganda]] which would impose the death penalty on homosexuals and on those supporting them were \"victimising\". He told the BBC that the proposed law \"tends to confuse all of homosexual relationships with what you call aggravated stuff and that's the problem\" but that the Anglican Communion was committed to recognising that gay people were valued by God.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8429699.stm Archbishop of York condemns Ugandan anti-gay bill] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305003930/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8429699.stm |date=5 March 2016 }} BBC</ref>  Previously, as area Bishop of Stepney, he was one of four English bishops who refused to sign the [[Cambridge Accord]]: an attempt in 1999 to find agreement on affirming certain human rights of homosexuals, notwithstanding differences within the church on the morality of homosexual behaviour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.changingattitude.org/cambridge_accord.htm |title=Cambridge Accord (with UK signatories and refusals to sign) |accessdate=27 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020219212448/http://www.changingattitude.org/cambridge_accord.htm |archivedate=19 February 2002 }}</ref> In 2012 he stated his opposition to government plans to legalise [[same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom]], asserting that \"Marriage is a relationship between a man and a woman, I don't think it is the role of the State to define what marriage is\" and \"We've seen dictators [redefine marriage] in different contexts and I don't want to redefine very clear social structures that have been in existence for a long time.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = Don't legalise gay marriage, Archbishop of York Dr John Sentamu warns David Cameron | last = Beckford | first = Martin | date = 27 January 2012 | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/9045796/Dont-legalise-gay-marriage-Archbishop-of-York-Dr-John-Sentamu-warns-David-Cameron.html | accessdate =28 January 2012 | work = The Telegraph | location=London}}</ref> At the same time, he expressed support for same-sex [[civil partnerships]]. \"They [<nowiki/>[[Civil partnership in the United Kingdom|civil partnerships]]] are in every respect in ethical terms an honourable contract of a committed relationship.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.archbishopofyork.org/news/news-archive-previous-years/response-marriage-and-civil-partnerships|title=A Response on Marriage and Civil Partnerships|last=Sentamu|first=John|date=17 May 2012|website=archbishopofyork.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, speaking to [[Piers Morgan]], Sentamu said that he would not call homosexuality a 'sin' and still supported civil unions while opposing same-sex marriage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ugchristiannews.com/archbishop-john-sentamu-says-he-would-never-describe-homosexuality-as-a-sin/|title=I would  \"never\" describe homosexuality as a sin \u2013 Archbishop John Sentamu|date=17 June 2016|work=UG Christian News|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref> \u201cI support civil partnerships because I think that\u2019s a matter of equality, and a matter of fairness, but for me, it was wrong for the Government to try to redefine the nature of marriage\" he said.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2016/06/15/archbishop-john-sentamu-homosexuality-is-not-a-sin-lgbt-people-were-created-in-gods-image-too/|title=Archbishop John Sentamu: Homosexuality is not a sin, LGBT people were created in God's image too |work=PinkNews |accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref> In 2017, Sentamu spoke out in favour of a motion at [[General Synod of the Church of England|General Synod]] to call for the government to ban the use of '[[Conversion therapy|conversion]]' therapy, a controversial practice meant to change a person's sexual orientation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/church-of-england-bishops-ban-gay-conversion-therapy-pride-2016-lgbt-rights-a7831391.html|title=Church of England bishops call for ban on gay conversion therapy|work=The Independent|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref> At the same session of General Synod, Sentamu supported a motion to offer \"welcome and affirmation\" for transgender persons as members of the Church of England.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.christiantoday.com/article/church-of-england-backs-special-services-marking-new-identities-for-transgender-people/110551.htm|title=Church of England backs special services marking new identities for transgender people|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nCommenting on [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]] and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Kate Middleton]]'s decision to live together before their wedding, Sentamu said that the couple's public commitment to live their lives together today would be more important than their past. He said that he had conducted wedding services for \"many cohabiting couples\" during his time as a vicar in south London, and said, \"We are living at a time where some people, as my daughter used to say, want to test whether the milk is good before they buy the cow.\"<ref name=\"marriage\"/>\n\nHe also said, \"For some people that's where their journeys are. But what is important, actually, is not to simply look at the past because they are going to be standing in the Abbey taking these wonderful vows: 'for better for worse; for richer for poorer; in sickness and in health; till death us do part.'\"<ref name=marriage />\n\nIn a speech to the House of Lords on 19 November 2007, he opposed elements of the [[Human Fertilisation and Embryology Act 2008|Human Fertilisation and Embryology Bill]] for seeking to remove a child's \"need for a father\" in the [[IVF]] process. He said: \"We are now faced with a Bill which is seeking to formalise the situation where the need for the ultimate male role model \u2013 that of the father \u2013 is removed in entirety.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.archbishopofyork.org/1281|title=Human Fertilisation and Embryology Bill|work=Press release containing text of speech|publisher=Archbishop of York's press office|date=19 November 2007|accessdate=7 April 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820071359/http://www.archbishopofyork.org/1281|archive-date=20 August 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== National Trust Egg Hunt ===\nIn 2017 he criticised the National Trust for \"airbrushing out\" religion from the National Trust Egg Hunt.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/04/03/easter-egg-row-church-england-accuses-national-trust-airbrushing/|title=Easter egg row: Church of England accuses National Trust of 'airbrushing' religion out of children's egg hunt|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n===Columnist===\nSentamu has contributed to ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]''<ref name=\"DT\">{{cite news|last=Walker|first=Tim|title=John Sentamu\u2019s Sunday service may be short|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/9109175/John-Sentamus-Sunday-service-may-be-short.html|accessdate=3 April 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=28 February 2012}}</ref> [[tabloid newspaper]], and in 2012 he contributed to the first edition of the ''Sun on Sunday''. All the income that he derives from journalism goes to St Leonard's Hospice in York, of which he is president.<ref name=\"DT\"/>\n\nIn September 2007, Sentamu wrote in his column that the parents of the missing [[Madeleine McCann]], were subject to a \"whispering campaign\" and were entitled to the [[presumption of innocence]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.archbishopofyork.org/1068?q=mccann|title=We must have faith for Maddie|work=Press release of article originally written for [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] newspaper|publisher=Archbishop of York's press office|date=4 July 2007|accessdate=7 April 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416202828/http://www.archbishopofyork.org/1068?q=mccann|archive-date=16 April 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Public baptisms===\nOn Easter Sunday 2008, Sentamu baptised 20 people by full immersion in a tank of water outside [[St Michael-le-Belfrey]] Church in York. Hundreds of people watched the ceremony.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/north_yorkshire/7310570.stm\n|title = Archbishop leads outdoor baptisms\n|accessdate =11 April 2008\n|date = 23 March 2008\n|work=BBC News \n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Skydive for the Afghanistan Trust===\nOn 6 June 2008, Sentamu completed a charity skydive from 12,500 feet with a member of the [[Parachute Regiment (United Kingdom)|Red Devils]] parachute team. The dive took place over Langar Airfield in [[Nottinghamshire]], with Sentamu aiming to raise \u00a350,000 for the Afghanistan Trust. Yorkshire businessman Guy Brudenell had challenged Sentamu to do the jump at a charity dinner and Brudenell also took part in the jump on the day.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/7439257.stm|title = Archbishop skydives for soldiers\n|accessdate =6 June 2008\n|date = 6 June 2008\n|work=BBC News \n}}\n</ref>  In recognition of what was described as his \"pluck\", Sentamu was later given honorary membership of the Parachute Regimental Association.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.thepress.co.uk/search/4144156.Paras_recognise_Dr_John___s_pluck/\n |accessdate =27 March 2009\n|date = 21 February 2009\n|title = Paras recognise Dr John\u2019s pluck\n|work=[[The Press (York)|The Press]]\n|publisher=Newsquest Media Group\n}}\n</ref>\n\nSentamu and Brudenell raised over \u00a375,000.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2083754/Archbishop-of-York,--John-Sentamu,-performs-skydive.html|title = Archbishop of York, John Sentamu, performs skydive\n|accessdate =6 June 2008\n|date = 6 June 2008\n|work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London\n| first1=Martin\n| last1=Beckford\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Hull Kingston Rovers===\nOn 15 April 2011 Sentamu addressed the crowd at [[Craven Park, Hull|Craven Park]] before the Engage [[Super League]] [[Rugby league]] match between [[Hull Kingston Rovers]] and [[Wigan Warriors]]. He asked the crowd to join him in prayer extolling the virtues of teamwork and harmony in sport. Afterwards he was presented with a Hull KR shirt.\n\n==Safeguarding clergy disciplinary measure complaint and police investigation==\n[[File:Protest at Oxford.jpg|thumb|Protest brochure]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Bishop of Oxford enthronement protest.JPG..jpg|left|thumb|200px]] -->In May 2016 Sentamu was one of six bishops accused of procedural misconduct by a victim of [[child sex abuse]] (the accusation was to do with how the complaint was handled; none of the six was involved in the abuse). Sentamu was named in the ''[[Guardian newspaper|Guardian]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=Senior Anglican clergy accused of failing to act on rape allegations|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jul/26/senior-anglican-clergy-accused-of-failing-to-act-on-allegations|accessdate=7 October 2016|work=The Guardian|date=26 July 2016}}</ref> and ''[[Church Times]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=Goddard Inquiry begins to sift through Church\u2019s evidence|url=https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2016/29-july/news/uk/goddard-inquiry-begins-to-sift-through-church-s-evidence|accessdate=7 October 2016|work=Church Times|date=29 July 2016}}</ref> alongside [[Peter Burrows]], [[Steven Croft (bishop)|Steven Croft]], [[Martyn Snow]], [[Glyn Webster]] and [[Roy Williamson (bishop)|Roy Williamson]], as subject of Clergy Disciplinary Measure complaints owing to their inaction on the survivor's disclosure. The bishops contested the complaints because they were made after the church's required one-year limit. Sentamu had acknowledged receipt of a letter from the survivor with an assurance of \"prayers through this testing time\". But according to the ''Guardian'' report, no action was taken against the alleged abuser nor support offered to the survivor by the church. A spokesperson for the archbishop said that Sentamu had simply acknowledged a copy of a letter addressed to another bishop. \"The original recipient of the letter had a duty to respond and not the archbishop\", the spokesperson said. All six bishops appeared on a protest brochure which the survivor handed out at Steven Croft's enthronement as Bishop of Oxford.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sex abuse survivors protest outside Christ Church enthronement and accuse bishop of ignoring rape claims|url=http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/news/14776196.Sex_abuse_survivors_protest_outside_Christ_Church_and_accuse_Bishop_of_Oxford_of_ignoring_rape_claims/?ref=mrb&lp=5|accessdate=7 October 2016|newspaper=The Oxford Times|date=30 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018 it was reported that Archbishop Sentamu and four other bishops were under investigation by [[South Yorkshire Police]] for failure to respond properly to a report of clerical child abuse. A memo from June 2013, seen by ''The Times'' and other media revealed that Sentamu had received the allegation but recommended that 'no action' be taken. The priest against whom the allegation was made went on to commit suicide the day before he was due in court in June 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Police investigate archbishop for \u2018failures\u2019 over child abuse claims|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/police-investigate-archbishop-for-failures-over-child-abuse-claims-289ngnt5h|accessdate=13 April 2018|agency=''The Times''|date=2 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Police look at bishops' 'failure to act' over sex abuse claims|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-43228491|accessdate=13 April 2018|agency=''BBC''|date=5 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sentamu ordered \u2018no action\u2019 against paedophile priest \u2013 leaving him to abuse again and commit suicide|url=http://archbishopcranmer.com/sentamu-ordered-no-action-paedophile-priest-leaving-abuse-commit-suicide/|accessdate=13 April 2018|agency=''Archbishop Cranmer''|date=6 March 2018}}</ref> The Archbishop of York's office said: {{quote |The diocese of York insists that Sentamu did not fail to act on any disclosures because that responsibility lay with Ineson's local bishop, [[Steven Croft (bishop)|Steven Croft]], who was at the time bishop of [[Sheffield]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Archbishop of York facing police investigation over failure to report abuse|url=https://www.christiantoday.com/article/archbishop-of-york-facing-police-investigation-over-failure-to-report-abuse/128016.htm|accessdate=13 April 2018|agency=''Christian Today''|date=2 April 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nA ''[[Guardian News|Guardian]]'' editorial contrasted Archbishop Sentamu's response to a statement from [[Justin Welby|Archbishop Welby]] at IICSA, the [[Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse]], in which Justin Welby stated {{quote |It is not an acceptable human response, let alone a leadership response to say \u201cI have heard about a problem, but \u2026 it was someone else\u2019s job to report it\u201d.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Guardian view of abuse in the church: a truly dreadful story|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/mar/22/the-guardian-view-of-abuse-in-the-church-a-truly-dreadful-story|accessdate=15 April 2018|agency=''The Guardian''|date=22 March 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nMatt Ineson, the victim and survivor at the heart of the case, has called for the resignations of Archbishop Sentamu and Bishop Steven Croft.<ref>{{cite web|title=Call for the Resignation of Archbishop John Sentamu and Bishop Steven Croft|url=http://www.thinkinganglicans.org.uk/archives/007826.html|website=Thinking Anglicans|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Styles==\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n* ''The [[Reverend]]'' John Sentamu (1979\u20131984)\n* ''The Reverend'' [[Doctor of Philosophy|Doctor]] John Sentamu (1984\u20131993)\n* ''The Reverend'' [[Honorary canon|Canon]] Doctor John Sentamu (1993\u20131996)\n* ''The [[Right Reverend]]'' Doctor John Sentamu (1996\u20132005)\n* ''His Grace The [[Most Reverend]] and [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom#Rights and privileges of members|Right Honourable]]'' Doctor John Sentamu, Lord Archbishop of York (2005\u2014present)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|John Sentamu}}\n* [http://www.birmingham.anglican.org/article/264/ '''Enthronement of the Archbishop of York''', Timetable of Events]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070207082524/http://itn.co.uk/news/ae43f9f81e0e3d34e1833bf85d3e9dd4.html ITN interview, 7 February 2007]\n* {{YouTube|I88Wy7otcrc|Archbishop of York cuts up his Dog Collar in Mugabe protest (VIDEO) 9 December 2007}}\n* [http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/y/19338/John%20Tucker%20Mugabi%20Sentamu+YORK.aspx ''Debrett's People of Today'']\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-rel|en}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Richard Chartres]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Stepney]]|years=1996\u20132002}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Stephen Oliver (bishop)|Stephen Oliver]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Mark Santer]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Birmingham]]|years=2002\u20132005}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[David Urquhart (bishop)|David Urquhart]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[David Hope, Baron Hope of Thornes|David Hope]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Archbishop of York]]<br />''(Primate of England)''|years=2005\u2013present}}\n{{S-aft|after=''[[Stephen Cottrell]], {{nowrap|archbishop-designate}}''}}\n{{s-prec|ew}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Buckland]]|as=[[Lord Chancellor]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Order of precedence in England and Wales#Archbishops.2C High Officers of State.2C et al.|Gentlemen]]<br /><small>''as Archbishop of York''</small>}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Boris Johnson]]|as=[[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{UK Order of Precedence (Gentlemen)}}\n{{Bishops of Stepney}}\n{{Bishops of Birmingham}}\n{{Archbishops of York}}\n{{Longford Lecturers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sentamu, John Tucker Mugabi}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Archbishops of York]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Stepney]]\n[[Category:Lords Spiritual]]\n[[Category:Ugandan clergy]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:21st-century Anglican archbishops]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Selwyn College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Ridley Hall, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Selwyn College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People associated with York St John University]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Cumbria]]\n[[Category:After Dark (British TV series) participants]]\n[[Category:Ugandan Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Makerere University alumni]]\n[[Category:Ugandan emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British Anglicans]]\n[[Category:English people of Ugandan descent]]\n[[Category:Black British religious leaders]]\n[[Category:The Sun (United Kingdom) people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Archbishop of York}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| honorific-prefix = {{pre-nominal styles|size=100%|MRevd|&RHPC}}\n| name = John Sentamu\n| honorific-suffix = <!---------- Please do not fill in here academic degrees according WP:MOSBIO ---------->\n| title = [[Archbishop of York]]<br />and [[Canterbury\u2013York dispute|Primate of England]]\n| image = Official portrait of The Lord Archbishop of York crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Sentamu in 2019\n| province = [[Province of York|York]]\n| diocese = [[Diocese of York|York]]\n| enthroned = 30 November 2005<ref name=\"enth\">{{cite news |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/north_yorkshire/4481796.stm | title = First black Archbishop enthroned | date = 30 November 2005 |work=BBC News  | accessdate =12 August 2006 }}</ref>\n| predecessor = [[David Hope, Baron Hope of Thornes|David Hope]]\n| ordination = 1979\n| consecration = 25 September 1996\n| consecrated_by = [[George Carey]]\n| other_post = [[Bishop of Stepney]] (1996\u20132002)<br />[[Bishop of Birmingham]] (2002\u20132005)\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name = John Tucker Mugabi Sentamu\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1949|6|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Kampala]], Uganda\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]<!-- As a matter of course and reasonable expectation: Wholly unreasonable (and malicious) to suspect that the Archbishop of York of the Church of England (\"Established Church\" in England) has not legally and formally acquired British nationality and British citizenship (likely) by a procedure called \"naturalisation\" or by some other means (made a British citizen by the Home Office, for and on behalf of the Secretary of State (Home Secretary)) some point during his life (probably long) before becoming Archbishop. -->\n| religion = [[Church of England]]\n| residence = [[Bishopthorpe Palace]], [[Bishopthorpe]], [[York]]\n| parents = John and Ruth Walakira<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2006-Ra-Z/Sentamu-John.html |title=Notable Biography |publisher=Notablebiographies.com |accessdate=30 April 2011}}</ref>\n| spouse = {{marriage|Margaret|1973}}\n| children = Two<ref name=bbckids>{{cite web|last1=Holmes|first1=Tara|title=Breaking the mould|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/christianity/people/johnsentamu_1.shtml|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=21 November 2014}}</ref>\n| profession = Cleric, lawyer\n| alma_mater = {{unbulleted list | [[Makerere University]] | [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]] | [[Ridley Hall, Cambridge]]}}\n| module        = {{Infobox officeholder | embed = yes\n |office         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br /><small>[[Lords Spiritual|Lord Spiritual]]</small>\n|term_start = 25 January 2006\n|term_end       =}}\n}}\n'''John Tucker Mugabi Sentamu''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|\u025b|n|t|\u0259m|u\u02d0}};<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phonetic-blog.blogspot.de/2012/10/an-archiepiscopal-mnemonic.html |title=an archiepiscopal mnemonic  |accessdate=10 October 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303235800/http://phonetic-blog.blogspot.de/2012/10/an-archiepiscopal-mnemonic.html |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref> {{IPA-lg|s\u02d0\u00e9\u02d0nt\u00e1m\u00fb|Luganda:}}; born 10 June 1949) is an Anglican bishop, serving as the 97th [[Archbishop of York]], [[Metropolitan (religion)|Metropolitan]] of [[Province of York|York]], and [[primate (bishop)|Primate]] of England. The position of Archbishop of York is the second most senior clerical position in the [[Church of England]] after that of the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], Primate of All England.\n\nBorn near [[Kampala]] in [[Uganda]], Sentamu studied law at [[Makerere University]] before gaining employment as an [[barrister|advocate]] of the [[Supreme Court of Uganda]]. Speaking out against the regime of President [[Idi Amin]], he was briefly imprisoned before fleeing in 1974 to the United Kingdom, where he devoted himself to [[Anglicanism]], beginning his study of [[theology]] at [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]], in 1976 and eventually gaining a doctorate in 1984. He studied for ordination at [[Ridley Hall, Cambridge]], and was ordained in 1979. In 1996 he was consecrated as the [[area bishop|area]] [[Bishop of Stepney]] and in 2002 moved to the position of [[Bishop of Birmingham]]. In 2005 he was appointed to the position of [[Archbishop of York]].\n\nSentamu expresses support for some traditionalist positions within the [[Church of England]], as he has publicly criticised [[multiculturalism]] and the legalisation of [[same-sex marriage]], but contrary to traditional Christian moral teaching he supports [[cohabitation]] before marriage, stating \"We are living at a time where some people ... want to test whether the milk is good before they buy the cow.\"<ref name=marriage>{{cite news|title=Archbishop backs William and Kate's decision to live together before marriage|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/royal-wedding/8481736/Royal-wedding-Archbishop-backs-William-and-Kates-decision-to-live-together-before-marriage.html|accessdate=3 April 2013|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=29 April 2011}}</ref> He has also received attention for his vocal criticism of former Zimbabwean president [[Robert Mugabe]].\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nSentamu was born in 1949 in a village near [[Kampala]], [[Uganda Protectorate|Uganda]], the sixth of thirteen children. He obtained a [[Bachelor of Laws]] at [[Makerere University]], [[Kampala]], and practised as an [[barrister|advocate]] of the High Court of Uganda until 1974, being briefly a judge of the High Court. In 1973, he married his wife Margaret.<ref name=vallely>{{cite news|last1=Vallely|first1=Paul|title=Dr John Sentamu: Next stop Canterbury?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/dr-john-sentamu-next-stop-canterbury-7624760.html|accessdate=21 November 2014|work=[[The Independent]]|date=7 April 2012}}</ref> Three weeks after his marriage, he incurred the wrath of the dictator [[Idi Amin]] and was detained for 90 days. In a speech in 2007, he described how during that time he had been \"kicked around like a football and beaten terribly\", saying \"the temptation to give up hope of release was always present\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.24dash.com/communities/20416.htm |title=''Archbishop tells his captivity story in call to free Alan Johnson'' |accessdate=20 November 2007 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926234859/http://www.24dash.com/communities/20416.htm |archivedate=26 September 2007 }}, 24dash.com. Retrieved 11 January 2009</ref> He fled his home country to arrive as an [[Immigration|immigrant]] in the [[United Kingdom]] in 1974.\n\n===Education and early ministry===\nSentamu studied theology at [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]] (Bachelor of Arts {BA} 1976, [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|Cambridge Master of Arts]] {MA Cantab} 1979, [[Doctor of Philosophy]] {PhD} 1984). He was baptized at Eden Baptist Church, Cambridge. He trained for the priesthood at [[Ridley Hall, Cambridge]], being ordained a priest in 1979. His doctoral thesis is entitled \"Some aspects of [[soteriology]], with particular reference to the thought of [[J. K. Mozley]], from an African perspective\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ulmss-newton.lib.cam.ac.uk/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?SC=Author&SA=Sentamu%2C%20John |title=University of Cambridge library catalogue |access-date=5 December 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003085608/https://ulmss-newton.lib.cam.ac.uk/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?SC=Author&SA=Sentamu%2C%20John |archive-date=3 October 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He worked as assistant chaplain at Selwyn College, as chaplain at a remand centre and as [[curate]] and [[vicar]] in a series of parish appointments.\n\nSentamu was [[consecrated]] a bishop on 25 September 1996, by [[George Carey]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], at [[St Paul's Cathedral]];<ref>{{Church Times | title = London welcomes bishops | archive = 1996_09_27_001 | issue = 6972 | date = 27 September 1996 | page = 1 | accessed = 26 June 2018 }}</ref> to serve as [[Bishop of Stepney]], a [[suffragan bishop|suffragan]] and [[area bishop]] in the [[Diocese of London]]. It was during this time that he served as advisor to the [[Stephen Lawrence]] Judicial Enquiry. In 2002 he chaired the [[Damilola Taylor]] review. That same year he was appointed [[Bishop of Birmingham]] where his ministry, according to the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[Rowan Williams]], was praised by \"Christians of all backgrounds\".{{citation needed|date=June 2012}} Sentamu became President of Youth for Christ in 2004 and President of the YMCA in April 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.archbishopofyork.org/780 |title=Biography |publisher=The Archbishop of York |accessdate=30 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722104742/http://www.archbishopofyork.org/780 |archive-date=22 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Archbishop of York===\nOn 17 June 2005 the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|prime minister's]] office announced Sentamu's translation to [[Diocese of York|York]] as the 97th archbishop.<ref name=\"appt\">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/4102582.stm | title = New Archbishop of York appointed |date =17 June 2005 |work=BBC News  | accessdate =12 August 2006 }}</ref> He was formally elected by the chapter of [[York Minster]] on 21 July,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=57706 |page=9331|date=19 July 2005}}</ref> legally confirmed as archbishop at [[St Mary-le-Bow]], London on 5 October,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140201190444/http://www.churchofengland.org/media-centre/news/2005/10/pr7305a.aspx Church of England \u2013 Sentamu: Confirmation as Archbishop of York] (Accessed 15 July 2013)</ref> and enthroned at York Minster on 30 November 2005 (the feast of [[Saint Andrew]]), at a ceremony with African singing and dancing and contemporary music, with Sentamu himself playing African drums during the service.<ref name=\"enth\" /><ref>{{cite news | url = http://politics.guardian.co.uk/homeaffairs/story/0,11026,1508879,00.html | title = First black Church of England archbishop appointed | date = 17 June 2005 | work=The Guardian | accessdate =12 August 2006 | location=London | first=Simon | last=Jeffery}}</ref> As Archbishop of York, Sentamu sits in the [[House of Lords]]<ref>[https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/archbishop_of_york They Work For You] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420231715/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/archbishop_of_york |date=20 April 2016 }}</ref> and was admitted, as a matter of course, to the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"deb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/search/results/19338/John%20Tucker%20Mugabi%20Sentamu+YORK.aspx |title=Debrett's People of Today \u2013 John Sentamu York |publisher=Debretts.com |date=6 October 1949 |accessdate=30 April 2011}}</ref> He was the first black archbishop in the Church of England.<ref name=\"enth\" /><ref name=\"appt\" />\n\n[[File:York Easter Sunday 2007.jpg|thumb|250px|left|John Sentamu outside York Minster on [[Easter Sunday]], 2007.]] \nFor a week in August 2006, Sentamu camped in York Minster, forgoing food in solidarity with those affected by the Middle East conflict, especially the children and other civilians killed and injured during the [[2006 Lebanon War]], when [[cluster bombs]] were used by Israeli forces.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/world/2006/0812/1155291283803.html | title = Anglican archbishop's solidarity fast | date = 12 August 2006 | work=The Irish Times | accessdate =12 August 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/help/3681938.stm |title=John Sentamu to fast |date=12 August 2006 |work=BBC News |accessdate=14 August 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060813215404/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/help/3681938.stm |archivedate=13 August 2006 }}<!-- BBC Video and Audio help page --></ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/g2/story/0,,1851757,00.html | title = Inside is a strange place to pitch a tent\u2026 | date = 17 August 2006 |work=The Guardian |location=UK | accessdate =17 August 2006  | first=Stephen | last=Bates}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 March 2007, Sentamu was installed as the first Chancellor of [[York St John University]]. On 1 June 2007 he was appointed as the first Chancellor of the [[University of Cumbria]]. He took up the position when the university opened on 1 August 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Archbishop becomes new chancellor|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/6711449.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=6 December 2011|date=1 June 2007}}</ref> In July 2009, he was awarded an honorary doctorate by [[University of Chester]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chester.ac.uk/node/6184 |title=Twelve of the University of Chester\u2019s recent triumphs |publisher=Chester.ac.uk |date=13 July 2010 |accessdate=29 November 2011}}</ref> On 15 July 2010, Sentamu was presented with an honorary degree from the [[University of York]] by the Provost of Vanbrugh College, [[David Efird]] of the Department of Philosophy,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-10656063 |work=BBC News  | title=Archbishop John Sentamu receives an honorary degree | date=15 July 2010}}</ref> and on 16 July 2010 was presented with an honorary degree from the [[University of Leeds]] by the chancellor of the university, [[Melvyn Bragg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leeds.ac.uk/info/30310/honorary_graduates/305/john_sentamu |title=John Sentamu \u2013 John Sentamu \u2013 University of Leeds |publisher=Leeds.ac.uk |date=16 July 2010 |accessdate=30 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608141223/http://www.leeds.ac.uk/info/30310/honorary_graduates/305/john_sentamu |archivedate= 8 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 July 2007, Sentamu was presented with an honorary degree from the [[University of Hull]] by the chancellor of the university, [[Virginia Bottomley]], at [[Hull City Hall]] during the graduation ceremony for graduands of the Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences.<ref>[http://www.hull.ac.uk/news/july07/archyork.html The University of Hull] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417131925/http://www.hull.ac.uk/news/july07/archyork.html |date=17 April 2009 }}</ref> On 19 July 2007 he was presented with an honorary degree (Doctor of Letters) from the [[University of Sheffield]] in recognition of his distinguished career as a scholar and theologian.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.shef.ac.uk/mediacentre/archbishop.html | title = Archbishop of York awarded honorary degree | date = 23 July 2007 | publisher=University of Sheffield | accessdate =23 July 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2007 Sentamu was awarded the \"Yorkshireman of the Year\" title by the [[Black Sheep Brewery]]. In his acceptance speech he praised the welcome he had received from the people of [[Yorkshire]] and made reference to the \"[[Haplogroup A (Y-DNA)#A1-P108|African-Yorkshire DNA connection]]\", joking that perhaps his parents had this in mind when they gave him the name \"Mugabi\", which, spelled backwards, is \"Ibagum\" (\"ee-by-gum\", a stock phrase popularly supposed to be used to express shock or disbelief in northern England).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dioceseofyork.org.uk/cgi/news/news.cgi?t=template&a=1186 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416063556/http://www.dioceseofyork.org.uk/cgi/news/news.cgi?t=template&a=1186 |url-status=dead |archivedate=16 April 2009 |title=Speech by the Most Revd & Rt Hon Dr John Sentamu on accepting the Yorkshire Man of the Year Award |date=26 October 2007 |publisher=The Diocese of York |accessdate=30 November 2007 }}</ref> In 2008 Archbishop [[Thurstan]] Church of England School in Hull was renamed [[Archbishop Sentamu Academy]] in his honour.\n\nIn October 2018, Sentamu announced his retirement, scheduled for 7 June 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Archbishop of York Dr John Sentamu to retire |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-45707419 |website=BBC News |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> In June 2019, he ordained his wife as a deacon.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Vicky |date=23 June 2019 |title=Archbishop of York to ordain new deacons - including his wife - at York Minster |url=https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/17722183.archbishop-of-york-to-ordain-new-deacons-including-his-wife-at-york-minster/ |work=[[The Press (York)|The Press]]|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nSentamu has spoken on issues including young people, the family, slavery, and injustice and conflict abroad.  In an early TV appearance in 1988 he joined, among others, [[Ray Honeyford]], [[Ann Dummett]] and [[Lurline Champagnie]] to discuss \"Race and the classroom\" on ''[[After Dark (TV series)|After Dark]]''.<ref>[[List of After Dark editions]], accessed 20 September 2012</ref> In November 2005 he sought re-discovery of English pride and cultural identity, stating that zeal for [[multiculturalism]] had sometimes \"seemed to imply, wrongly for me, 'let other cultures be allowed to express themselves but do not let the majority culture at all tell us its glories, its struggles, its joys, its pains'.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2-1882591,00.html | title = Multiculturalism has betrayed the English, Archbishop says | date = 30 November 2005 |work=The Times |location=UK | accessdate =12 August 2006 | first=Ruth | last=Gledhill |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060513154744/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2-1882591,00.html|archive-date=13 May 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> \nIn 2006 he claimed that the [[BBC]] was frightened of criticising [[Islam]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2006/11/14/nmuslim14.xml|accessdate=24 March 2007|date=15 November 2006|title=BBC frightened of criticising Islam, says archbishop|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|first=Jonathan|last=Petre|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061114195539/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=%2Fnews%2F2006%2F11%2F14%2Fnmuslim14.xml|archive-date=14 November 2006|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Sentamu featured prominently in the British press because of his comments on the treatment of detainees in [[Guantanamo Bay Naval Base]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.independent.co.uk/world/americas/article346214.ece|title=The Americans are breaking international law...|date=18 February 2006|work=The Independent|location=UK|accessdate=30 November 2006|first1=Ian|last1=Herbert|first2=Ben|last2=Russell|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070106161441/http://news.independent.co.uk/world/americas/article346214.ece|archivedate=6 January 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Poverty===\nSentamu regrets that many low paid workers are not paid enough to lift them and their families out of [[poverty]]. \n{{quote|The issue  is one that strikes to the heart of the moral fabric of our society. For the very first time the majority of households in poverty in Britain have at least one person working. The nature of poverty in Britain is changing dramatically. For millions of hard-pressed people, work is no longer a route out of poverty. (...) Low pay is a scourge on our society, and we all pay for it. Low pay costs the taxpayer between 3.6 and 6 billion pounds a year in tax credits, in-work benefits and lost tax receipts. And as disposable income available to the lowest paid reduces, so too does the demand in the economy.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/dr-john-sentamu-for-millions-of-people-work-is-no-longer-a-way-out-of-poverty-9117824.html Dr John Sentamu: For millions of people, work is no longer a way out of poverty]</ref>}}\n\n{{quote|Once upon a time you couldn't really be living in poverty if you had a regular income, you could find yourself on a low income, yes. But that is not longer so. You can be in work and still live in poverty.<ref name=\"Guradian19/11/13\">[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/nov/19/food-poverty-archbishop-york-john-sentamu Archbishop attacks UK food poverty]</ref>}}\n\nSentamu believes that food poverty is causing [[malnutrition]] in the UK.  In 2013, he said that \"last year more than 27,000 people were diagnosed as suffering from malnutrition in Leeds \u2013 not Lesotho, not Liberia, not Lusaka but Leeds?\" and feels these reports \"disgrace us all, leaving a dark stain on our consciences\".<ref name=\"Guradian19/11/13\" /> Government welfare reform were, \n{{quote|beginning to bite \u2013 with reductions in housing benefit for so-called under-occupation of social housing, the cap on benefits for workless householders and single parents, and the gradual replacement of the disability living allowance with a personal independence payment\".<ref name=\"Guradian19/11/13\"/>}}\n\n===General election===\nIn the run up to the [[2017 United Kingdom general election]] [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[Justin Welby]] and John Sentamu campaigned over the need to address [[Poverty in the United Kingdom#Poverty in the UK in the 21st century|poverty]], [[Education in the United Kingdom|education]], housing and [[National Health Service|health]].  The archbishops stressed the importance of \"education for all, of urgent and serious solutions to our housing challenges, the importance of creating communities as well as In the run up to the [[2017 United Kingdom general election]], and a confident and flourishing health service that gives support to all - especially the vulnerable - not least at the beginning and end of life.\"<ref>[http://www.itv.com/news/2017-05-06/archbishops-of-canterbury-and-york-raise-election-concerns-in-letter/ Archbishops of Canterbury and York raise election concerns in letter]</ref>\n\n===Stop and search===\nIn 2000, Sentamu, then [[Bishop of Stepney]], was stopped by a [[City of London Police]] officer near [[St Paul's Cathedral]].  Sentamu claimed it was the eighth time he had been questioned by police in eight years, and that he was the only Church of England bishop to have been stopped by police in this way.<ref name=guardian-Jan-2000>{{cite news|last=Dodd|first=Vikram|title=Black bishop 'demeaned' by police search|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2000/jan/24/race.world|accessdate=27 September 2011|newspaper=The Guardian|date=24 January 2000|location=London}}</ref> In a 2010 debate in the [[House of Lords]], Sentamu was critical of the standards of \"reasonable grounds to suspect\" applied by police.<ref name=hansard-1278>{{cite web|title=Volume No. 720 - 27 July 2010 : Column 1278|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201011/ldhansrd/text/100727-0002.htm#10072739000568|work=Hansard|publisher=Houses of Parliament|accessdate=27 September 2011|date=27 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===\"Chocolate Trinity\" comments===\nOne of Sentamu's favourite references is to \"The Chocolate Trinity\" of God-fearing [[Quaker]] capitalists who were involved in developing the chocolate industry:<ref name=\"Lecture notes\">[http://www.dioceseofyork.org.uk/cgi/news/news.cgi?t=template&a=908 Bishop\u2019s lecture notes on York Diocese website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416072157/http://www.dioceseofyork.org.uk/cgi/news/news.cgi?t=template&a=908 |date=16 April 2009 }}.</ref><ref name = \"Ebor\">His [[Ebor Lecture]] in [[York Minster]] (13 September 2006).</ref>\n\n* [[George Cadbury]]: \"More than just a sweet man\"\n* [[Joseph Rowntree (Philanthropist)|Joseph Rowntree]]:  \"an adventurer to the end of life, forever peering forward, never content with what had been achieved.\"\n* [[Joseph Storrs Fry II]] (J. S. Fry):  \"the very model of the pre-1860 Quaker, with his [[plain dress]] a relic of the past and a reflection of his narrow conservative approach to both religion and business.\"\n\n===Robert Mugabe===\n[[Image:John Sentamu York City v. AFC Telford United 1.png|thumb|right|Sentamu wearing a clerical shirt without its white insert, 2009]]\nOn 9 December 2007, during a live television interview with [[Andrew Marr]] on [[BBC One]], Sentamu made a protest against [[Zimbabwe]]an president [[Robert Mugabe]]. Sentamu took the white insert off his [[clerical collar|clerical shirt]] and cut it up stating that: {{quote |as an Anglican, this is what I wear to identify myself that I'm a clergyman. Do you know what Mugabe has done? He's taken people's identity and literally if you don't mind, cut it to pieces. This is what he's actually done, to a lot of\u2014and in the end there's nothing. So as far as I'm concerned from now on I'm not going to wear a dog collar until Mugabe's gone.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7135087.stm |title=Archbishop makes Zimbabwe protest |accessdate=9 December 2007 |work=BBC News  | date=9 December 2007}}</ref>}}His protest followed criticism against Mugabe at the EU-Africa summit in [[Lisbon]].\n\nIn December 2008, Sentamu again spoke out against Mugabe, saying \"The time has come for Robert Mugabe to answer for his crimes against humanity, against his countrymen and women and for justice to be done\".<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7769546.stm\n|title = Archbishop urges Mugabe overthrow.\n|accessdate =6 December 2008\n|date = 6 December 2008\n|work=BBC News \n}}\n</ref>\n\nOn 26 November 2017, Sentamu returned to ''The Andrew Marr Show'' and kept his promise to reinstate his dog collar following Robert Mugabe's resignation earlier in the week.\n\nMarr presented him with an envelope containing the original cut up pieces of collar. Of it he said \n{{quote |You know, Andrew, I could attempt to put this one back together using superglue, but it would be a pretty ropey collar. And I actually think the lesson for Zimbabwe is the same. They just can't try and stitch it up. Something more radical, something new needs to happen.</small><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-42128073|title=Archbishop ends 10-year Mugabe protest|date=2017-11-26|work=BBC News|accessdate=2017-11-26}}</ref>}}\n\nHe then put on a new dog collar which he had brought with him. He also said it could be possible for Zimbabweans to forgive Mr Mugabe. \"Mugabe needs to say at some point to Zimbabweans: 'Forgive me'. He's a very, very intelligent man and I think he is capable of doing it.\"\n\n===Financial crisis===\nIn September 2008, Sentamu and the Archbishop of Canterbury, [[Rowan Williams]], spoke out against opportunistic stock market trading. Sentamu compared those who practised [[short selling]] of [[HBOS]] shares, driving the share prices down, to \"bank robbers\".<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7634641.stm\n|title = Archbishops attack City practices\n|accessdate =25 September 2008\n|date = 25 September 2008\n|work=BBC News \n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Sexuality and marriage===\n[[File:Archbishop of York, Rev Grace Sentamu-Baverstock (28449165817) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Sentamu and his daughter Grace Sentamu-Baverstock]]\nSentamu, born in Uganda, said [[Uganda Anti-Homosexuality Bill|laws being debated in Uganda]] which would impose the death penalty on homosexuals and on those supporting them were \"victimising\". He told the BBC that the proposed law \"tends to confuse all of homosexual relationships with what you call aggravated stuff and that's the problem\" but that the Anglican Communion was committed to recognising that gay people were valued by God.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8429699.stm Archbishop of York condemns Ugandan anti-gay bill] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305003930/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8429699.stm |date=5 March 2016 }} BBC</ref>  Previously, as area Bishop of Stepney, he was one of four English bishops who refused to sign the [[Cambridge Accord]]: an attempt in 1999 to find agreement on affirming certain human rights of homosexuals, notwithstanding differences within the church on the morality of homosexual behaviour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.changingattitude.org/cambridge_accord.htm |title=Cambridge Accord (with UK signatories and refusals to sign) |accessdate=27 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020219212448/http://www.changingattitude.org/cambridge_accord.htm |archivedate=19 February 2002 }}</ref> In 2012 he stated his opposition to government plans to legalise [[same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom]], asserting that \"Marriage is a relationship between a man and a woman, I don't think it is the role of the State to define what marriage is\" and \"We've seen dictators [redefine marriage] in different contexts and I don't want to redefine very clear social structures that have been in existence for a long time.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = Don't legalise gay marriage, Archbishop of York Dr John Sentamu warns David Cameron | last = Beckford | first = Martin | date = 27 January 2012 | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/9045796/Dont-legalise-gay-marriage-Archbishop-of-York-Dr-John-Sentamu-warns-David-Cameron.html | accessdate =28 January 2012 | work = The Telegraph | location=London}}</ref> At the same time, he expressed support for same-sex [[civil partnerships]]. \"They [<nowiki/>[[Civil partnership in the United Kingdom|civil partnerships]]] are in every respect in ethical terms an honourable contract of a committed relationship.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.archbishopofyork.org/news/news-archive-previous-years/response-marriage-and-civil-partnerships|title=A Response on Marriage and Civil Partnerships|last=Sentamu|first=John|date=17 May 2012|website=archbishopofyork.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, speaking to [[Piers Morgan]], Sentamu said that he would not call homosexuality a 'sin' and still supported civil unions while opposing same-sex marriage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ugchristiannews.com/archbishop-john-sentamu-says-he-would-never-describe-homosexuality-as-a-sin/|title=I would  \"never\" describe homosexuality as a sin \u2013 Archbishop John Sentamu|date=17 June 2016|work=UG Christian News|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref> \u201cI support civil partnerships because I think that\u2019s a matter of equality, and a matter of fairness, but for me, it was wrong for the Government to try to redefine the nature of marriage\" he said.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2016/06/15/archbishop-john-sentamu-homosexuality-is-not-a-sin-lgbt-people-were-created-in-gods-image-too/|title=Archbishop John Sentamu: Homosexuality is not a sin, LGBT people were created in God's image too |work=PinkNews |accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref> In 2017, Sentamu spoke out in favour of a motion at [[General Synod of the Church of England|General Synod]] to call for the government to ban the use of '[[Conversion therapy|conversion]]' therapy, a controversial practice meant to change a person's sexual orientation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/church-of-england-bishops-ban-gay-conversion-therapy-pride-2016-lgbt-rights-a7831391.html|title=Church of England bishops call for ban on gay conversion therapy|work=The Independent|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref> At the same session of General Synod, Sentamu supported a motion to offer \"welcome and affirmation\" for transgender persons as members of the Church of England.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.christiantoday.com/article/church-of-england-backs-special-services-marking-new-identities-for-transgender-people/110551.htm|title=Church of England backs special services marking new identities for transgender people|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nCommenting on [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]] and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Kate Middleton]]'s decision to live together before their wedding, Sentamu said that the couple's public commitment to live their lives together today would be more important than their past. He said that he had conducted wedding services for \"many cohabiting couples\" during his time as a vicar in south London, and said, \"We are living at a time where some people, as my daughter used to say, want to test whether the milk is good before they buy the cow.\"<ref name=\"marriage\"/>\n\nHe also said, \"For some people that's where their journeys are. But what is important, actually, is not to simply look at the past because they are going to be standing in the Abbey taking these wonderful vows: 'for better for worse; for richer for poorer; in sickness and in health; till death us do part.'\"<ref name=marriage />\n\nIn a speech to the House of Lords on 19 November 2007, he opposed elements of the [[Human Fertilisation and Embryology Act 2008|Human Fertilisation and Embryology Bill]] for seeking to remove a child's \"need for a father\" in the [[IVF]] process. He said: \"We are now faced with a Bill which is seeking to formalise the situation where the need for the ultimate male role model \u2013 that of the father \u2013 is removed in entirety.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.archbishopofyork.org/1281|title=Human Fertilisation and Embryology Bill|work=Press release containing text of speech|publisher=Archbishop of York's press office|date=19 November 2007|accessdate=7 April 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820071359/http://www.archbishopofyork.org/1281|archive-date=20 August 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== National Trust Egg Hunt ===\nIn 2017 he criticised the National Trust for \"airbrushing out\" religion from the National Trust Egg Hunt.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/04/03/easter-egg-row-church-england-accuses-national-trust-airbrushing/|title=Easter egg row: Church of England accuses National Trust of 'airbrushing' religion out of children's egg hunt|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n===Columnist===\nSentamu has contributed to ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]''<ref name=\"DT\">{{cite news|last=Walker|first=Tim|title=John Sentamu\u2019s Sunday service may be short|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/9109175/John-Sentamus-Sunday-service-may-be-short.html|accessdate=3 April 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=28 February 2012}}</ref> [[tabloid newspaper]], and in 2012 he contributed to the first edition of the ''Sun on Sunday''. All the income that he derives from journalism goes to St Leonard's Hospice in York, of which he is president.<ref name=\"DT\"/>\n\nIn September 2007, Sentamu wrote in his column that the parents of the missing [[Madeleine McCann]], were subject to a \"whispering campaign\" and were entitled to the [[presumption of innocence]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.archbishopofyork.org/1068?q=mccann|title=We must have faith for Maddie|work=Press release of article originally written for [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] newspaper|publisher=Archbishop of York's press office|date=4 July 2007|accessdate=7 April 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416202828/http://www.archbishopofyork.org/1068?q=mccann|archive-date=16 April 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Public baptisms===\nOn Easter Sunday 2008, Sentamu baptised 20 people by full immersion in a tank of water outside [[St Michael-le-Belfrey]] Church in York. Hundreds of people watched the ceremony.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/north_yorkshire/7310570.stm\n|title = Archbishop leads outdoor baptisms\n|accessdate =11 April 2008\n|date = 23 March 2008\n|work=BBC News \n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Skydive for the Afghanistan Trust===\nOn 6 June 2008, Sentamu completed a charity skydive from 12,500 feet with a member of the [[Parachute Regiment (United Kingdom)|Red Devils]] parachute team. The dive took place over Langar Airfield in [[Nottinghamshire]], with Sentamu aiming to raise \u00a350,000 for the Afghanistan Trust. Yorkshire businessman Guy Brudenell had challenged Sentamu to do the jump at a charity dinner and Brudenell also took part in the jump on the day.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/7439257.stm|title = Archbishop skydives for soldiers\n|accessdate =6 June 2008\n|date = 6 June 2008\n|work=BBC News \n}}\n</ref>  In recognition of what was described as his \"pluck\", Sentamu was later given honorary membership of the Parachute Regimental Association.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.thepress.co.uk/search/4144156.Paras_recognise_Dr_John___s_pluck/\n |accessdate =27 March 2009\n|date = 21 February 2009\n|title = Paras recognise Dr John\u2019s pluck\n|work=[[The Press (York)|The Press]]\n|publisher=Newsquest Media Group\n}}\n</ref>\n\nSentamu and Brudenell raised over \u00a375,000.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2083754/Archbishop-of-York,--John-Sentamu,-performs-skydive.html|title = Archbishop of York, John Sentamu, performs skydive\n|accessdate =6 June 2008\n|date = 6 June 2008\n|work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London\n| first1=Martin\n| last1=Beckford\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Hull Kingston Rovers===\nOn 15 April 2011 Sentamu addressed the crowd at [[Craven Park, Hull|Craven Park]] before the Engage [[Super League]] [[Rugby league]] match between [[Hull Kingston Rovers]] and [[Wigan Warriors]]. He asked the crowd to join him in prayer extolling the virtues of teamwork and harmony in sport. Afterwards he was presented with a Hull KR shirt.\n\n==Safeguarding clergy disciplinary measure complaint and police investigation==\n[[File:Protest at Oxford.jpg|thumb|Protest brochure]]<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Bishop of Oxford enthronement protest.JPG..jpg|left|thumb|200px]] -->In May 2016 Sentamu was one of six bishops accused of procedural misconduct by a victim of [[child sex abuse]] (the accusation was to do with how the complaint was handled; none of the six was involved in the abuse). Sentamu was named in the ''[[Guardian newspaper|Guardian]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=Senior Anglican clergy accused of failing to act on rape allegations|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jul/26/senior-anglican-clergy-accused-of-failing-to-act-on-allegations|accessdate=7 October 2016|work=The Guardian|date=26 July 2016}}</ref> and ''[[Church Times]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=Goddard Inquiry begins to sift through Church\u2019s evidence|url=https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2016/29-july/news/uk/goddard-inquiry-begins-to-sift-through-church-s-evidence|accessdate=7 October 2016|work=Church Times|date=29 July 2016}}</ref> alongside [[Peter Burrows]], [[Steven Croft (bishop)|Steven Croft]], [[Martyn Snow]], [[Glyn Webster]] and [[Roy Williamson (bishop)|Roy Williamson]], as subject of Clergy Disciplinary Measure complaints owing to their inaction on the survivor's disclosure. The bishops contested the complaints because they were made after the church's required one-year limit. Sentamu had acknowledged receipt of a letter from the survivor with an assurance of \"prayers through this testing time\". But according to the ''Guardian'' report, no action was taken against the alleged abuser nor support offered to the survivor by the church. A spokesperson for the archbishop said that Sentamu had simply acknowledged a copy of a letter addressed to another bishop. \"The original recipient of the letter had a duty to respond and not the archbishop\", the spokesperson said. All six bishops appeared on a protest brochure which the survivor handed out at Steven Croft's enthronement as Bishop of Oxford.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sex abuse survivors protest outside Christ Church enthronement and accuse bishop of ignoring rape claims|url=http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/news/14776196.Sex_abuse_survivors_protest_outside_Christ_Church_and_accuse_Bishop_of_Oxford_of_ignoring_rape_claims/?ref=mrb&lp=5|accessdate=7 October 2016|newspaper=The Oxford Times|date=30 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018 it was reported that Archbishop Sentamu and four other bishops were under investigation by [[South Yorkshire Police]] for failure to respond properly to a report of clerical child abuse. A memo from June 2013, seen by ''The Times'' and other media revealed that Sentamu had received the allegation but recommended that 'no action' be taken. The priest against whom the allegation was made went on to commit suicide the day before he was due in court in June 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Police investigate archbishop for \u2018failures\u2019 over child abuse claims|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/police-investigate-archbishop-for-failures-over-child-abuse-claims-289ngnt5h|accessdate=13 April 2018|agency=''The Times''|date=2 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Police look at bishops' 'failure to act' over sex abuse claims|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-43228491|accessdate=13 April 2018|agency=''BBC''|date=5 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sentamu ordered \u2018no action\u2019 against paedophile priest \u2013 leaving him to abuse again and commit suicide|url=http://archbishopcranmer.com/sentamu-ordered-no-action-paedophile-priest-leaving-abuse-commit-suicide/|accessdate=13 April 2018|agency=''Archbishop Cranmer''|date=6 March 2018}}</ref> The Archbishop of York's office said: {{quote |The diocese of York insists that Sentamu did not fail to act on any disclosures because that responsibility lay with Ineson's local bishop, [[Steven Croft (bishop)|Steven Croft]], who was at the time bishop of [[Sheffield]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Archbishop of York facing police investigation over failure to report abuse|url=https://www.christiantoday.com/article/archbishop-of-york-facing-police-investigation-over-failure-to-report-abuse/128016.htm|accessdate=13 April 2018|agency=''Christian Today''|date=2 April 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nA ''[[Guardian News|Guardian]]'' editorial contrasted Archbishop Sentamu\u2019s response to a statement from [[Justin Welby|Archbishop Welby]] at IICSA, the [[Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse]], in which Justin Welby stated {{quote |It is not an acceptable human response, let alone a leadership response to say \u201cI have heard about a problem, but \u2026 it was someone else\u2019s job to report it\u201d.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Guardian view of abuse in the church: a truly dreadful story|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/mar/22/the-guardian-view-of-abuse-in-the-church-a-truly-dreadful-story|accessdate=15 April 2018|agency=''The Guardian''|date=22 March 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nMatt Ineson, the victim and survivor at the heart of the case, has called for the resignations of Archbishop Sentamu and Bishop Steven Croft.<ref>{{cite web|title=Call for the Resignation of Archbishop John Sentamu and Bishop Steven Croft|url=http://www.thinkinganglicans.org.uk/archives/007826.html|website=Thinking Anglicans|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Styles==\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n* ''The [[Reverend]]'' John Sentamu (1979\u20131984)\n* ''The Reverend'' [[Doctor of Philosophy|Doctor]] John Sentamu (1984\u20131993)\n* ''The Reverend'' [[Honorary canon|Canon]] Doctor John Sentamu (1993\u20131996)\n* ''The [[Right Reverend]]'' Doctor John Sentamu (1996\u20132005)\n* ''His Grace The [[Most Reverend]] and [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom#Rights and privileges of members|Right Honourable]]'' Doctor John Sentamu, Lord Archbishop of York (2005\u2014present)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|John Sentamu}}\n* [http://www.birmingham.anglican.org/article/264/ '''Enthronement of the Archbishop of York''', Timetable of Events]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070207082524/http://itn.co.uk/news/ae43f9f81e0e3d34e1833bf85d3e9dd4.html ITN interview, 7 February 2007]\n* {{YouTube|I88Wy7otcrc|Archbishop of York cuts up his Dog Collar in Mugabe protest (VIDEO) 9 December 2007}}\n* [http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/y/19338/John%20Tucker%20Mugabi%20Sentamu+YORK.aspx ''Debrett's People of Today'']\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-rel|en}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Richard Chartres]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Stepney]]|years=1996\u20132002}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Stephen Oliver (bishop)|Stephen Oliver]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Mark Santer]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Birmingham]]|years=2002\u20132005}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[David Urquhart (bishop)|David Urquhart]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[David Hope, Baron Hope of Thornes|David Hope]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Archbishop of York]]<br />''(Primate of England)''|years=2005\u2013present}}\n{{S-aft|after=''[[Stephen Cottrell]], {{nowrap|archbishop-designate}}''}}\n{{s-prec|ew}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Buckland]]|as=[[Lord Chancellor]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Order of precedence in England and Wales#Archbishops.2C High Officers of State.2C et al.|Gentlemen]]<br /><small>''as Archbishop of York''</small>}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Boris Johnson]]|as=[[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{UK Order of Precedence (Gentlemen)}}\n{{Bishops of Stepney}}\n{{Bishops of Birmingham}}\n{{Archbishops of York}}\n{{Longford Lecturers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sentamu, John Tucker Mugabi}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Archbishops of York]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Stepney]]\n[[Category:Lords Spiritual]]\n[[Category:Ugandan clergy]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:21st-century Anglican 